<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Ambassador to Egypt Suspended for Three </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot ambassador to Egypt
Charalambos Kapsos was suspended Tuesday by the government for
allegedly charging entrance fees and importing wine into Egypt
when holding a party.
</P>
<P>
An official announcement said Cyprus' Public Service
Commission, responsible for hiring civil servants, took the
decision following a proposal by Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides.
</P>
<P>
The allegation against Charalambos Kapsos were carried in
Cyprus' Politis daily last week, which said the ambassador charged
a 60 U.S. dollar entrance fee for each gust, imported dozens of
cases of wine and invited Romanian dancers when holding a
"bouzouki night" party in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Following the allegation, Kasoulides recalled the ambassador
and ordered an inquiry although Kapsos has denied the accusations
in letters to the press.
</P>
<P>
As for the 372 cartons of wine he is reported to have taken to
Cairo, Kapsos argued that they were for long-term use, adding that
some bottles have been used for Cyprus nights while the rest are
stored at his residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
