<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Hostage Drama Meets Its Happy End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone rebel kidnappers have
freed the rest of their captives Tuesday, ending a five-day
hostage crisis, according to information reaching here from
Freetown, the capital.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's Information Minister Julius Spencer said at a
press conference that the former junta soldiers had freed 15 west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) along with a U.N. military
observer and some 200 civilians Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were heading toward Freetown and "the hostage
drama is over in Sierra Leone," said Spencer.
</P>
<P>
The release came shortly after the capture of Idriss Kamara, a
high ranking official of the former military junta led by Johnny
Koroma who had ruled the country for 10 months before being driven
out by the Nigeria-led ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Kamara was captured by his former junta colleagues in their
camp Friday after he tried to negotiate a hostage release. He was
freed Sunday morning with five U.N. drivers, but returned that
night to help negotiate the release of 13 more hostages.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers, believed to be followers of Koroma, released
Sunday 19 people out of a jungle hideaway where one freed hostage
said as many as 2, 000 disenchanted members of the former junta
are based.
</P>
<P>
"They treated us fine," said Chernor Bangura, a journalist for
Sierra Leone state television Sunday. "We were given one meal a
day and tea in the morning," he added.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappings of the about 35 people took place last
Wednesday during what was to have been a handover of some
civilians seized by the gunmen during the civil war. The hostages
includes U.N. observers, ECOMOG soldiers, aid workers and
journalists.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers freed last Thursday the first batch of their
captives and let them carry messages demanding food and medical
supplies and the release of Koroma, who they claimed had been
detained by the Foday Sankoh-led Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
rebel faction.
</P>
<P>
But Koroma denied later that he was a prisoner of the RUF and
promised to personally intervene to dissolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the RUF and the former junta soldiers has
been straining, though Sankoh keeps calling Koroma the "number two
figure" of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Many of Koroma's men might feel excluded when the RUF signed
the July 7 Lome peace accord on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
Koroma, a former officer of government force, claiming himself
the head of state of Sierra Leone in 1997 through a coup, allied
himself with the RUF, which has been fighting successive
governments since 1991.
</P>
<P>
But 10 months later, he was flushed out by the Nigeria-led
ECOMOG and the unseated President Tejan Kabbah was reinstated.
Since then the two factions of the rebels had fought against
Kabbah's government joint- handedly until the ceasefire in June
this year and the ensuing peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
