<HEADLINE> Iraqi Solar Eclipse-Observing Camp Bombed by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 10 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi camp for observing
total solar eclipse in the north of the country was bombed by
U.S. and British warplanes on Tuesday, in which a number of
civilians were killed or injured, the Iraqi News Agency INA
reported.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted a spokesman for the preparatory committee
supervising the observation of total solar eclipse as saying
that U.S. and British warplanes fired three missiles at the
camp which is located to the north of Mosul, some 500 kilometers
north of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:30 (0630 GMT), formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace flew over Mosul and
bombed the camp while some satellite channels witnessed and
filmed the bombardment.
</P>
<P>
"This criminal act represents the aggressors' hatred against
the Iraqi people and their persistence on preventing Iraq from
covering this natural scientific phenomenon," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Specialists say that on August 11, total solar eclipse can
be observed in the northern Iraqi province of Neineva, where,
as they say, is an ideal location for observing this phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many foreign and Arab astronomers, satellite
channels and news reporters gathered in Mosul, capital city of
Neineva province, to witness this phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi military spokesman said earlier Tuesday that U.S.
and British warplanes bombed civilian installations in northern
and southern Iraq, injuring three civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
