<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- One man was shot to death by police near Jerusalem
on Tuesday when he steered his car twice to the sidewalk at a bus
stop in an attempt to run down people.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police said that at least nine people were wounded in
the incident and all of them were soldiers and police.
</P>
<P>
Paramedics said that one soldiers was injured seriously and
the others were hurt lightly. (BC-Israel-Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) on Tuesday
refused to accept a timetable that permits Israel to complete its
withdrawal from the West Bank by February 15 next year.
</P>
<P>
It was aimed at prolonging by seven months the third phase of
Israeli withdrawal under the Wye river accord signed between
Israel and the Palestinians last October, said Palestinian chief
negotiator Saed Erekat. (BC-Palestine-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Visiting Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said here
Tuesday he was confident the Middle East peace process would be
back on its right track with tangible progress.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his meeting with Jordanian King
Abdullah Bin Hussein to discuss bilateral ties and the latest
developments in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that he believed tangible progress would be achieved in
the coming stage in Israeli-Arab peace talks on all tracks. But he
did not eleborate. (BC-Jordan-Israel-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- After consulting with treasury and central bank
heads, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Tuesday set next year's
deficit target at 2.5 percent of the Gross Domestic Product and
annual inflation at 3-4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Barak decided that the government's economic policy goals
would be "the achievement of sustainable growth and ending the
current deep and lengthy recession," the prime minister's office
said in a statement. (BC-Israel-Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- An Iraqi camp for observing total solar eclipse in
the north of the country was bombed by U.S. and British warplanes
on Tuesday, in which a number of civilians were killed or injured,
the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted a spokesman for the preparatory committee
supervising the observation of total solar eclipse as saying that
U.S. and British warplanes fired three missiles at the camp which
is located to the north of Mosul, some 500 kilometers north of
Baghdad. (BC-Iraq-US Attacks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
