<HEADLINE> U.S. Freezes Assets of Afghan airline Ariana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
blocked assets of Afghanistan's Ariana national airline in
retaliation of the Taliban movement for its protection of
Saudi-born guerrilla leader Osama bin Laden, the White House
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has designated Ariana Afghan Airlines under
the Taliban sanctions today, blocking all of Ariana's assets
within U.S. jurisdiction," National Security Council spokesman
David Leavy said, adding the move would freeze roughly 500,000
U.S. dollars in assets held by the airline.
</P>
<P>
Leavy said the move also prevented U.S. companies and
individuals from doing business with the airline.
</P>
<P>
"These sanctions are in response to the Taliban's continuing
provision of safe haven to Osama bin Laden and his terrorist
network," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States on July 6 banned trade with
Taliban-controlled parts of Afghanistan for its protection of
bin Laden, who was accused of masterminding the bombings of
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
