<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Protest Against MP Allowances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- the Umbrella Labor Union (ULU) for
Nigerian workers Tuesday staged a demonstration in front of the
national legislature here in the capital to protest the
"outrageous" furniture allowances approved for the 469-member
legislature.
</P>
<P>
The union, representing a diversity of the country's labor
unions, disrupted the sitting of the lower chamber to protest the
award announced last week in the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, each of the 109-member Senate is
to get 3.5 million naira (about 37,000 US dollars) while their
counterparts in the 360-member House would get 2.5 million naira
(26,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Union President Adams Oshiomole led the workers, who were
originally barred by armed policemen who restricted the
demonstrators to the first gate to the sprawling complex.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's demonstration added to the growing pressure on
members of the two-chamber legislature to reject the allowances to
furnish their residence, vacated last month by civil servants to
pave way for the legislators.
</P>
<P>
Branding the awards "repulsive, provocative and princely
lifestyles in the midst of pervasive and abject poverty," the
Union president said it could not be justified with the country's
economic realities. He dismissed the parliamentarians as living
in "an illusory ivory tower", and reminded them of the realities
of the Nigerian economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria is today a poverty afflicted nation, per capita income
is about 260 dollars per annum and the minimum wage is 3,000
naira," he said.
</P>
<P>
Oshiomole warned that labor may be forced to abandon its
assumption that government finances could not sustain increased
public sector wages.
</P>
<P>
The unions, which settled for the 3,000 naira (about 32 US
dollars) minimum wage early this year after claims the government
would not afford a higher wage, would review "appeals for
sacrifice and belt tightening as hypocrisy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
