<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Sets Deficit, Inflation Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 10 (Xinhua) -- After consulting with
treasury and central bank heads, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Tuesday set next year's deficit target at 2.5 percent of the
Gross Domestic Product and annual inflation at 3-4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Barak decided that the government's economic policy goals
would be "the achievement of sustainable growth and ending the
current deep and lengthy recession," the prime minister's office
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Barak met with Finance Minister Avraham Shochat and Governor
of the Bank of Israel Yaakov Frenkel before convening his cabinet
to discuss the budgetary framework for 2000. The ongoing cabinet
meeting will last late into the night.
</P>
<P>
The 2.5 percent deficit target is lower than the expected
3-3.25 percent for 1999, but it is still above the legal target of
2 percent, which is also mandated by the European Union for its
members.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry has said the 0.5 percentage increase of
the deficit target over the original 2 percent stems primarily
from an overly-optimistic tax-revenue forecast.
</P>
<P>
Barak decided that the deficit will be gradually decreased to
no more than 1.5 percent of the GDP, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The budget will emphasize investment in infrastructure and
implementing necessary structural reforms," it said, adding that
the objective is to reduce the public sector share in the economy
while encouraging private sector's involvement to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
The budget includes a proposed 5.8 billion shekels (about 1.4
billion dollars) cut in the budgets for various ministries, which
has customarily raised objection among cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
Some ministers charged that the budget contains no
innovations, pointing to the fact that the proposal foresees no
significant drop in unemployment next year.
</P>
<P>
Barak has promised to create 300,000 new jobs over the next
four years. The Treasury said 55,000 new jobs would be created
next year under the new budget, reducing the jobless rate to 8.7
percent from an expected 8.9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
But Labor Minister Eli Yishai said this was not enough. "If the
government doesn't take steps now to create jobs and solve the
unemployment problem, the economy will have to grow at a rate of
more than 7 percent in 2001 - and this is a completely impossible
task," he told the Haaretz daily.
</P>
<P>
The budget target for deficit and inflation was an apparent
compromise between Shochat and Frenkel, who have been at odds
over the monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Shochat has urged Frenkel to lower the interest rate, which
stands at 11 percent after cutting twice this year, to stimulate
economic growth. He cited the expected inflation rate of 2-3
percent in 1999 as a good environment for the interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Israeli economy grew by 1.5 percent in 1998, the lowest growth
rate in the past decade. The Finance Ministry has proposed a 3
percent growth for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
But Frenkel has maintained that a tight monetary policy is
needed to restrict inflation, which soared to 8.6 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
In the statement issued by his office, Barak said that he
attaches great importance to coordination between "the two
economic policy arms," referring to the Treasury and the central
bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
