<HEADLINE> 3 Iraqi Civilians Injured in U.S.-British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqi civilians were
injured on Tuesday in U.S.-British warplanes attacks on civilian
facilities in northern and southern Iraq, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:00 (0600 GMT) seven
formations of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace
violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil
provinces and attacked some civilian facilities in the region,
injuring two civilians.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired
missiles at the enemy planes and repulsed them to their base
in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that at 10:55 (0655 GMT) 12 formations of U.S.
and British warplanes coming from the Saudi and Kuwaiti bases
violated southern Iraqi airspace over Basra, Thi-Qar, Muthana and
Misan provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy warplanes bombed some civilian installations in
the region and injured another civilian, he said, adding that
Iraqi anti-aircraft units repulsed the enemy planes.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made 11,220 sorties over the two no-fly
zones in Iraq, and have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led
western allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed
aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south from attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
