<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Canadian company Occidental Petroleum, which is
undertaking large petroleum projects in Yemen, has announced that
fields in Yemeni Massila region has made remarkable production in
the second quarter of 1999, reaching 210,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The company emphasized that its current successful drilling
program in the region helped increase about 40 million barrels of
oil per day in Yemen at a cost of two dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The company also said that confirmed reserves in Massila region
would suffice exploitation for over five years, the Alam Al Yom
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Al Gof company of Saudi Arabia on agricultural
development has completed the feasibility studies for the
construction of a beet sugar plant with an annual production of
about 13,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by Tuesday's Alam Al Yom said the
company will officially announced to break ground for the plant
this month.
</P>
<P>
The statement said half of the construction fund of the plant,
which needs 600 million rials (160 million dollars), will depend
on a loan from the Saudi industrial development fund. The
remaining 50 percent will be provided by Saudi businessmen and
investors and several local banks.
</P>
<P>
It added that raw materials for the plant will come from the
company's sugar beet plantations.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and the World Bank Tuesday signed an
agreement to allow the latter to officially open a permanent
office in Beirut in a bid to facilitate economic assistance to the
country .
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Lebanese Finance Minister George
Korom and Inder Sud, the World Bank director of North Africa
and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Korom said the setting-up of
office will speed up the utilization of World Banks loans and aid
provided to Lebanon for its on-going administrative and tax
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The office will also help make easy the communication and
coordination between Lebanese government and the bank, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The European Union (EU) has pledged 425,000 Euro
(roughly 400,000 dollars) to finance a Lebanese Finance Ministry's
program for administrative, financial and tax reforms.
</P>
<P>
EU Ambassador in Beirut Dimitri Kourkoulas and Lebanese
Finance Minister Georges Korom signed the memorandum of
understanding Monday, under which the ministry will receive the
EU donation.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to set up a training center to prepare
Lebanese finance ministry's staff for the introduction of the
value added tax in the near future.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Trans-Mediterranean Airways (TMA), Lebanon's only air
cargo company, has announced that it would begin a regular flight
to Doha, Qatar, at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of our strategy to increase our network and
expand into the Gulf because of the push to increase exports out
of Beirut," TMA's chairman Fadi Saad said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Qatar, Bahrain and Saudi Arabia had previously been served on
an ad-hoc basis and only when there was enough load, Saad added.
</P>
<P>
TMA began its regular flight to Dubai last week and will make
the similar flight to Bahrain by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
