<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses Iran of Politicalizing POWs Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi Foreign Ministry on
Tuesday accused Iran of trying to politicalize the issue of
prisoners of war (POWs) and use it as a pressing card over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed spokesman for the foreign ministry said in a
statement that Iraq dealt with the POWs issue according to the
Islamic rules and the international law and claimed that Iraq had
released all Iranian POWs according to the 1949 Geneva Treaty
concerning the POWs.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused Iranian officials of "resorting to lies
to cover facts" regarding the issue of POWs and linking it with
other issues, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iranian government tried to cover up lies it had
said to Iranians that those Iranians missing in actions were POWs
in Iraq in order to lessen the real numbers of the Iranians killed
during the 1980-1988 Iraq-Iran war.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iranian officials asked to exchange Iraqi POWs
for ordinary Iranian prisoners including women and the elderly in
order to give Iranian media the impression that these ordinary
prisoners were POWs.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Iraq's firm policy on the POWs issue is not
to link it with other issues, which was proved by the release of
318 Iranian POWs in April 1998 and 53 others in March 1999 under
the observation of the International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been an outstanding obstacle that stands
in the way of normalizing ties between the two former foes.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors fought a bitter eight-year war in the 1980s
in which some 1 million people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accuses Iran of still retaining 13,000 Iraqi POWs while
Iran says there are 5,000 Iranian POWs in Iraq's prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
