<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African, Zambian Officials to Visit Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- South African and Zambian
officials are expected in Congo's third largest city Kisangani
with a mandate of verifying the problems of leadership within the
main rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), rebel
sources in Kisangani said.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma and
Zambian State House Minister Eric Silwamba are visiting the area
at a time when tension has mounted between Ugandan People's
Defense Forces (UPDF) and the RCD rebels based in the town, the
Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, as Silwamba was getting ready to return to
Kisangani he had visited early on Thursday to assess the balance
of power between the RCD- Goma of Emile Ilunga, and his rival
ousted rebel leader professor Wamba dia Wamba, the UPDF had
mobilized the residents of that city to come out to show their
support for Wamba.
</P>
<P>
The RCD rebels said that the population refused, prompting the
UPDF to deploy tanks, APCs, and heavy artillery before attacking
rebel positions. The UPDF was fought back, losing a dozen of its
soldiers, while RCD rebels deplored five wounded, among whom was
the head of intelligence, Commander Slyvain Mbuki.
</P>
<P>
According to RCD rebels, the UPDF is in control of two hotels
in the town, and the local bank, but the other sections in the
town are firmly in the hands of RCD rebels including the Kisangani
main airport.
</P>
<P>
"This new verification mission is just useless because Silwamba
had noticed himself that Wamba was just a mere creation of some
regional powers whose aim is to torpedo the peace process," Emile
Ilunga, RCD leader told RNA from the rebel stronghold of Goma in
eastern Congo bordering Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the RCD rebels have accused Uganda of
fostering territorial ambitions over the eastern part of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo. "These people (Ugandans) came
pretending to support our struggle, but now they have shown their
true colors. They are just a force of occupation," Ilunga further
charged.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in eastern Congo alleged that the UPDF is
openly looting the riches of that rich area of the congo, where
timber, coffee, diamonds, and customs revenues go into the pockets
of some senior civil and military officials of President Yoweri
Museveni's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, the Rwandan government has expressed
outrage following a continued campaign against Rwandan troops
stationed in northeastern Congo fuelled by Ugandan media.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has denied reports by the state-run New Vision of Monday
claiming that 12 Rwandan soldiers and over 35 rebels had died in
Saturday clashes.
</P>
<P>
''We never engaged the UPDF during its fighting with RCD
rebels,'' Rwandan government spokesman, Lt Col. Wilson Rutayisire
told RNA, explaining that just four of Rwandan soldiers were
slightly injured by a fragment from UPDF's shellings.
</P>
<P>
RCD rebels have also refuted New Vision's report that 35 of
their men were killed and the RCD-Goma Deputy-Commander, along
with over 200 others were arrested by Wamba's forces.
</P>
<P>
''This is mere fabrication,'' said Rutayisire. ''It is an
attempt by UPDF commanders to create confusion in Kisangani with
the aim of confusing the verification mission which was expected
to visit Kisangani over the week- end,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
According to a Rwandan army officers in Kisangani, the reality
is that the UPDF suffered heavy losses on the contrary. The bodies
which were seen on the spot amounted to 12, but many more could
have been carried away by UPDF soldiers in disarray. 
</P>
</TEXT>
