<HEADLINE> Conflicts to Dominate SADC Summit in Mozambican </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The conflicts in Angola and the
Democratic Republic of Congo are expected to dominate the agenda
of the summit of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
in Mozambican capital Maputo next week.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuend revealed this in Maputo
tuesday at a briefing on the 1999 summit of the heads of state or
government of the SADC.
</P>
<P>
Mbuend noted that the theme of this year's summit is "SADC in
the Next Millennium: Working Together for Peace, Progress and
Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The relations between Angola and Zambia, the issue of Lesotho
and general elections in the region are also to be discussed at
the summit.
</P>
<P>
The Maputo meeting will review performance of the member states
in the past year, the executive secretary said, adding that the
SADC growth rate of 1.7 percent in 1998 was quite disappointing
when compared with the sound growth of 2.7 percent in 1997 and
over four percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mbuend pointed out that the continuation of the armed conflicts
in Angola and the DRC has impact negatively on the economic
stability, macro- economic management and investor confidence in
the directly involved countries as well as the region at large.
</P>
<P>
Before the summit, there will be meetings of Standing Committee
of Senior Officials, Finance Committee and Council of Ministers
from Tuesday to Saturday, he said.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, the regional leaders will celebrate the SADC
Day, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community now has 14 members,
namely Angola, Botswana, Democratic Congo, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
