<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-10 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says 55,438 Iraqi POWs Released Since 1981 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran said Tuesday that the latest
talks on prisoners of war (POWs) with Iraq put the number of
registered Iraqi POWs in Iran at two, with the fate of three
others being under investigation.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency,
Brigadier General Abdullah Najafi, head of the Commission on
Iranian POWs, told reporters that the number was "eventually"
decided by the two sides during the talks in Baghdad from July 24
to August 3.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has released 55,438 Iraqi prisoners of war
since 1981 on 103 occasions, while Iraq freed 39,417 Iranian POWs
in the same period on 70 occasions.
</P>
<P>
The two sides started to resolve the issue of POWs long after
the end of their eight-year bloody war from 1980 to 1988, in which
some 1 million people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
Najafi said their talks were marked by two phases. In the
first, between 1994 and 1997, no progress was made, but Iran
unilaterally released Iraqi POWs five times to show its good will.
</P>
<P>
He said fundamental steps were taken for removal of
disagreements between the two countries in the second phase from
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
A Red Cross list puts the number of unregistered Iraqi POWs in
Iran at 972, of whom some have sought asylum in Iran, some have
died and the fate of 666 others is under investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
As to a list presented to the Red Cross by Iraq, Najafi said it
contained 3,146 names, but only 2,525 were actual. But he said
fate of 2,283 of them is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq reduced the number of Iranian POWs as mentioned in
the Red Cross list to 2,923 from 3,100. The list is under
investigation and Iraq should clarify the fate of those POWs, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian, Tanzanian Defense Ministers to Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The defense ministers of
Burundi and Tanzania are expected to meet in Kigoma, northwest of
Tanzania, Wednesday to discuss security issues along the 230-km
long common border, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Burundi's state-owned Radio Bujumbura as
saying Tuesday afternoon that military experts from both countries
are already in discussions to prepare for the ministerial meeting,
which Burundi has been calling for over a year.
</P>
<P>
The Burundians attributed the delay of the ministerial meeting
to Tanzania's failure to keep its promised schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi government has continued to complain about deadly
incursions by armed people from Tanzania and back to their bases
after the army has crushed them.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is urgently necessary to avoid dangerous
escalation.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the issue of security which will feature high
on the agenda is linked to the presence of thousands of Burundi
refugees in Tanzania where Burundian rebels recruit fighters.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 Burundi Hutu refugees live in refugee camps
in the region of Kigoma in west Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months the repatriation has slackened down, but
now it is gaining momentum in areas northeast of Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hutu Rebels Raid South of Burundian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Fighting broke out between the
Burundian government troops and Hutu rebels Tuesday morning in the
suburbs of Kanyosha, south of capital Bujumbura, the Rwanda News
Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"Heavy gunfire which echoed in the capital caused the
population to panic and many fled toward the center of the city,"
military sources was quoted as saying in the Burundi capital.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that by late afternoon, the situation had
returned to normal and people had started to return home.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties on both sides in this renewed rebel
attack was not known, the report said.
</P>
<P>
When the rebels launched the attack on Kanyosha market toward
10:00 a.m. in small groups, they were repulsed, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the Burundian government troops have
mounted mop-up operations against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The province of Rural Bujumbura is considered a hotbed of the
armed Hutu rebellion which is engaged in inciting disobedience to
the central administration.
</P>
<P>
The six-year-old Burundi ethnic conflict has allegedly claimed
over 150, 000 lives, mostly civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
