<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Issues Bulletin Guiding Peacekeeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Secretariat Tuesday issued a bulletin in a bid to set out
"fundamental principles and rules of international humanitarian
law" applicable to U.N. peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin, entitled "Secretary-General's Bulletin Observance
by United Nations Forces of International Humanitarian Law," will
go into effect starting August 12, which coincides with the 50th
anniversary of the Geneva Conventions, a senior U.N. official
said.
</P>
<P>
The nine-page and 10-section bulletin said, "The fundamental
principles and rules of international humanitarian law set out in
this bulletin are applicable to United Nations forces when in
situation of armed conflict they are actively engaged therein as
combatants, to the extent for the duration of their engagement."
</P>
<P>
The senior U.N. official told a press conference here that the
bulletin provisions are only applicable to U.N. peacekeepers, who
are involved in a combat situation, rather than U.N. civilian
police, who "are normally unarmed."
</P>
<P>
"The places like Somalia, Rwanda and Bosnia demonstrate that
even peacekeepers, in certain situations, unavoidably became
involved in a combat situation," said the senior official.
</P>
<P>
"In case of violations of international humanitarian law,
members of the military personnel of a United Nations Force are
subject to prosecution in their national courts," the bulletin
said.
</P>
<P>
"The violators will be tried in their own national courts
because there is no U.N. tribunal which has jurisdiction over the
members of peacekeeping operations," he said, adding that the
trial will be conducted in accordance with the national
legislation.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations Force shall make a clear distinction at all
times between civilians and combatants and between civilian
objects and military objectives," the bulletin said. "Military
operations shall be directed against combatants and military
objectives."
</P>
<P>
"Attacks on civilians or civilian objectives are prohibited,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General sees the document as a necessary
evolution of the United Nations peacekeeping practices," he said,
adding that the origin of this document goes back to 1995, when
the International Commission of Red Cross raised an initiative in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
However, some languages and contents contained in this bulletin
remain controversial to a number of countries, he said. Some
Northern countries have "philosophical difficulties" with the
document "because for them, it is very difficult to conceive the
U.N. peacekeeping operations, by their very nature, can have its
members involved in a combat situation."
</P>
<P>
Anyway, "the document will be effective as the
Secretary-General has the very authority to promulgate it," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls on India, Pakistan to Exercise Restraint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday expressed regret at the loss of life resulting
from India's downing of a Pakistani plane and called on both
countries to "exercise maximum restraint."
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general regrets the loss of life following the
downing of a Pakistani aircraft by the Indian Air Force," Annan
said in a statement issued through his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The statement came in response to the shooting down by an
Indian combat aircraft of a Pakistani maritime patrol aircraft
that India said had strayed into its airspace.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan said the unarmed plane was shot down well within its
territory and that all 16 aboard had been killed. It reserved the
right "to make an appropriate response in self-defence."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman said Annan was "increasingly concerned at
the repeated incidents between India and Pakistan and urges that
the differences between them be resolved by peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
"He calls on both countries to exercise maximum restraint," the
satement said, "The secretary-general looks forward to an early
resumption of the bilateral dialogue between the two countries in
the spirit of the Lahore Declaration."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani and Indian prime ministers promised in Lahore in
February this year to intensify efforts to resolve all issues
between them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
