<HEADLINE> Four Independent MPs Re-join Malawi's Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- All four independent members of
parliament (MPs) of Malawi have re-joined the ruling United
Democratic Front (UDF), the Malawi News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the National Assembly Sam Mpasu disclosed this in
parliament Monday as Malawi's parliamentary budget session
1999/2000 deliberations continued.
</P>
<P>
The MPs are Martha Nasho, Friday Kalisinje, Justin Mokowa and
Roy Commcy who went to parliament as independents.
</P>
<P>
They ran as independent in the June 15 parliamentary and
presidential elections after they lost in UDF's primaries.
</P>
<P>
Mpasu explained that the development has come in the work of
letters which were submitted to his office from the MPs in which
they expressed their wish to join the ruling party again.
</P>
<P>
There is no legal barrier to prevent them from joining the UDF
since they didn't belong to any political party, said the speaker.
</P>
<P>
Mpasu then formally welcomed them back to the ruling party and
requested them to leave opposition bench and sit on the
government's side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
