<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi, Zambia to Re-draw Boundaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Survey departments of Malawi and
Zambia will this week re-demarcate land starting from where Zambia
borders Malawi in Mchinji, a central district, the Malawi News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There has been no proper boundary between the two countries and
as a result disputes have arisen among the people along the area
popularly known as no man's land, District Surveyor in Mchinji,
Ekinal Gonkho, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"At present we are using a watershed following a line of
highland separating river systems between the two countries as our
boundary," said Gonkho.
</P>
<P>
The surveyor said that people from both countries along this
watershed cultivate in the area, claiming that they belong to
nobody's.
</P>
<P>
"It is this situation that has forced us to physically
demarcate the land so that people along the watershed should know
where they exactly belong to," Gonkho said, adding that the new
boundary will be recognized by pillars or beacons to be built one
kilometer apart if the area is forest and 500 meters if it is
within settlement areas.
</P>
<P>
The surveyor said that bilateral talks on the demarcation
exercise started in 1994 and the two governments came to an
agreement early this year to start the exercise in the second week
of August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Indian Forces on Alert After Downing Pakistan Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian armed forces were put
in a "state of alert" in the entire western sector bordering
Pakistan following the shooting down of an "intruding" Pakistani
naval aircraft Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister George Fernandes warned neighboring Pakistan
that any violation of the Indian air space would be treated as a
"hostile act" and any intruding Pakistani aircraft would be shot
down.
</P>
<P>
He gave details of the air incident, saying that the Pakistani
pilot had "indulged in a hostile act by taking a turn towards the
Indian fighter aircraft and challenging it."
</P>
<P>
"The moment this happened the IAF (Indian Air Force) fighter
fired an air-to-air missile, hitting one of the engines of the
intruding Pakistani plane," Fernandes told the press here.
</P>
<P>
"Since the area was covered with thick clouds, the fighter
could not see where the Pakistani plane went down," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that IAF choppers had now reached the crash site and
were trying to extricate the wreckage which lay in the marshy area
in the Sir Creek region of Kutch in India's Western state of
Gujarat.
</P>
<P>
Asserting that the Pakistani plane had fallen within Indian
territory, Fernandes said his country would not allow any
Pakistani aircraft to reach the area or violate its airspace.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that about three Pakistani helicopters had
attempted to approach the area carrying what Islamabad described
as international observers but had to return after IAF warnings.
But he did not say when.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he considered that the incident had led to an
escalation of tension between the two neighbors, Fernandes said,
"I will not say there is any escalation. The aircraft intruded
without notice and was shot down."
</P>
<P>
He said efforts were on to find out with what motive the
aircraft had violated the Indian airspace.
</P>
<P>
An Indian Air Force official said that the Pakistani aircraft,
a French-made Breguet Atlantique which has a range of about 9,000
kilometers, was capable of carrying two "AS 12 or AM 39" Exocet
missiles, besides torpedoes and depth charges.
</P>
<P>
With one of its Atlantique being shot down, Pakistan now has
three of these aircraft along with three long-range U.S.-made P3C
Orion planes for maritime reconnaissance.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a spokesman of the Defense Ministry announced that IAF
combat planes shot down a Pakistan navy's anti-submarine and
reconnaissance aircraft after it intruded into the Indian air
space at 11:25 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The intruding Pakistani aircraft was detected by IAF ground
radar at 10:57 a.m. and was immediately intercepted by two MiG-21
aircraft, which took off from Naliya airbase in Gujarat, 10
kilometers south of the international border inside the Indian
territory, the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
When the IAF fighters closed in to identify and signal the
Pakistani aircraft to land at an Indian base nearby, the
four-engine French-built Atlantique aircraft acted "in a hostile
manner by turning into our fighters," he said.
</P>
<P>
"At that stage, the Atlantique was shot down by an air-to-air
missile which hit it on the port engine which caught fire," said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
While India said the wreckage of the Pakistan plane was found
by IAF helicopters two kilometers inside the Indian border,
Pakistan reportedly claimed that it had been located within their
area near Badin, some 300 kilometers northeast of Karachi.
</P>
<P>
Highly-placed Indian Navy sources said that the navy had been
put in a "state of enhanced vigilance" and was keeping a watch on
possible Pakistani reaction following the shooting down of the
plane.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India (PTI), the Directors
General for Military Operations (DGMOs) of the two countries spoke
to each other on the hotline after the downing of the Pakistani
plane.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the talks between the two DGMOs in the afternoon,
Fernandes said the Indian DGMO, Lt. Gen. N. C. Bij, who informed
his Pakistani counterpart Lt. Gen. Tauquir Zia of the incident,
was told that Pakistan was aware that its aircraft had been shot
down.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Pakistan said the aircraft was
carrying 16 navy personnel comprising six under-training officers
and 10 sailors, all of whom were confirmed dead by Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an unnamed Pakistani Naval official as saying
that the plane went missing at 11:30 a.m. Pakistan time and
helicopters sent out to search it sighted the wreckage on the
ground near Badin "inside the international border on the
Pakistani side." 
</P>
</TEXT>
