<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission Reports Progress to Reaching Goal in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Exactly eight weeks after
the international community arrived in Kosovo, a Serbian province,
to help rebuild the war-torn region, leaders of the main
components of the United Nations Interim Administrative Mission in
Kosovo (UNMIK) said that despite formidable challenges, the U.N.
mission was on track towards fulfilling its key tasks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference in the provincial capital
of Pristina, representatives of UNMIK's "four pillars" -- civil
administration, humanitarian affairs, institution building and
reconstruction -- reported on their efforts to make tangible
progress on all four fronts, U.N. officials said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dominique Vian, deputy U.N. special representative for civil
administration, said the goal of having a U.N. presence in all
municipalities was on its way to being fulfilled, either with U.N.
officials in advisory positions or in direct administrative roles,
as in the case of Pristina, Prizren and Pec.
</P>
<P>
"Now, life has come back to relative normalcy, services are
functioning, although in limited manner," Vian said.
</P>
<P>
All U.N. regional administrators had been in place for a month,
guiding efforts to rebuild civil service structures and establish
mechanisms for democratization, he said. Some 30 judges had been
appointed by the u.N. and were already working.
</P>
<P>
Reporting on the growing U.N. civilian police presence in
Kosovo, Vian said 602 officers were already on the ground. UNMIK
civilian police had begun joint patrols with the international
peacekeepers, known as KFOR, over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
As for the progress in institution building, another U.N.
deputy special representative, Daan Everts, said that the opening
of a police academy in Vucitrn was one of the main priorities.
</P>
<P>
The first courses for 200 local police cadets was scheduled to
begin on August 30, said Everts, who, as the U.N. deputy special
representative for institution building, heads the UNMIK component
led by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dennis McNamara, the U.N. deputy special representative for
humanitarian affairs, said with more than 90 percent of the
Kosovar refugees having returned home, UNMIK was now focusing on
providing adequate shelter.
</P>
<P>
To address the enormous need before the onset of winter, the
humanitarian community was providing thousands of tons of shelter
material, including nearly 80,000 shelter kits, said McNamara, The
U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights coordinates the UNMIK
humanitarian "pillar."
</P>
<P>
Joan Pearce of the European Union (EU) said that the EU, as
coordinator of the UNMIK reconstruction component, was also
concerned with ensuring adequate housing, as well as water and
power supply before winter.
</P>
<P>
UNMIK's advance party arrived in Kosovo on June 15, five days
after the U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution which
authorizes the UNMIK's position as the supreme civilian
administration before an elected autonomous authorities takes
office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
