<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Foresees Tangible Progress in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said here Tuesday he was confident the Middle East
peace process would be back on its right track with tangible
progress.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his meeting with Jordanian King
Abdullah Bin Hussein to discuss bilateral ties and the latest
developments in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that he believed tangible progress would be achieved in
the coming stage in Israeli-Arab peace talks on all tracks. But he
did not eleborate.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Abdullah called on Israel to abide by all
agreements it signed with the Palestinians to move forward the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah described, in particular, the "Wye River accord,
signed in October 1998, as a basic issue to rebuild confidence in
the peace process and to resume peace talks between Israel and
other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Wye Accord, under which Israel should have pulled out its
troops from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in three stages
by the end of January, was suspended in early December only after
the first phase was implemented.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on Syrian and Lebanese tracks have been stalled
since 1996 after hardline Israeli former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu took office.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also called on parties concerned to take advantage of
what he saw as positive atmosphere which arose from the May
election victory of Ehud Barak in Israel to create a new momentum
in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy said the new Israeli government headed by Barak valued the
active role played by Jordan through King Abdullah`s efforts and
wide-ranging contacts with parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting, Levy held talks with his Jordanian
counterpart Abdel-Ilah al-Khatib on the peace process in the
region and bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Their talks touched upon bilateral ties in all fields,
especially economic, trade, water cooperation, Jordan's official
news agency Petra said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Khatib also called on Israel to comply
with all agreements it signed with parties concerned to achieve a
just, durable and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers agreed to continue their
consultations on bilateral ties and the Middle East peace process
in future meetings.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been playing as a mediator in the Arab-Israeli peace
talks since he signed peace treaty with Israel in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
