<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rejects Saudi Mad Cow Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday
rejected reported Saudi Arabian claims that its beef products
could be infected with mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have mad cow disease in South Africa -- we never
have," South African Press Association quoted an Agriculture
Ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gideon Bruckner, director of food safety and veterinary public
health in Agriculture Ministry, said his country could not confirm
media reports that Saudi Arabia had banned beef imports from South
Africa because of concerns over the disease.
</P>
<P>
He said the Saudi government had over the past three or four
months been refusing to accept South African beef imports.
</P>
<P>
"They have made all sorts of claims, including that our meat is
infected with rinderpest -- which has been eradicated at the turn
of the century," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They can give no scientific reasons. There is a snake in the
grass."
</P>
<P>
Bruckner said Agriculture and Land Affairs Minister Thoko
Didiza has been asked to take up the matter at a political level.
</P>
<P>
"We are not so much concerned about our Saudi Arabian exports,
as these are but a fraction of our international exports. What
concerns us more is the message going out to other importing
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bruckner said South Africa had very strict controls over
imports from countries affected by mad cow disease, and
continuously monitored its own cattle for signs of the sickness.
</P>
</TEXT>
