<HEADLINE> All Remaining Hostages in Sierra Leone Released - UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) - Rebels in Sierra Leone has
released all remaining civilian and military hostages on Tuesday,
a British Foreign Office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We're very pleased everyone has come out safely," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said United Nations officials had told Britain's High
Commission in Freetown, the capital city of Sierra Leone, that
around 200 civilians, 20 Nigerian peacekeepers and a U.N. military
observer had been freed.
</P>
<P>
All the released hostages had reached a control post run by the
West African peacekeeping force on the road to Freetown, he said.
</P>
<P>
The release ended a week-long crisis triggered by last week's
capture of around 40 foreigners who had set out to secure the
release of the Sierra Leone civilians.
</P>
<P>
The hostages, part of a United Nations-led negotiating team,
were seized on Wednesday. They had gone to the Okra Hills, about
60 kilometres from Freetown, to try to persuade the rebels to
release about 100 children abducted earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers, who said they were members of Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council, former members of the government army who
rebelled and took control of the country in a military coup in
1997, demanded a stake in the peace settlement and to be
readmitted to the Sierra Leonean army.  
</P>
