<HEADLINE> Botswana Banks Increase Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Both Barclays Bank and
Standard Chartered Bank (StanChart) in Botswana have reported
significantly increased earnings in the first six months of 1999,
South African Press Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two banks largely underpin the Botswana Stock Exchange, and
account for 48.52 percent of market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax profits were 46.1 million pula (10.1 million U.S.
dollars) for Barclays from 39.0 million (8.5 million dollars) and
for StanChart 46.4 million pula (10.2 million dollars) against
34.2 million pula (7.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Barclays increased its dividend by 29.4 percent to a net 11
thebe, but StanChart held its at 50.5 thebe net because of
increased retention of profit to fund continuing growth. One pula
equals 100 thebe.
</P>
<P>
Both banks increased their loan base substantially. Barclays'
loans and advances were up 68.9 percent to 1,315 million pula
(287.7 million dollars) and StanChart up 29.8 percent to 878
million pula (192 million dollars). 
</P>
