<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Transport and Communication Committee of the
Alexandria Local Council has denied any recession in Egyptian
ports.
</P>
<P>
A recent report indicated Egyptian ports handled 52 million
tons of cargo in 1998, an increase of 17 million tons from 1997,
local press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said big increase, both in passengers and cargo,
prompted the government to embark on the development of Egyptian
ports and the establishment of national projects aimed at
increasing traffic capability.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The third phase of a food aid project in north Sinai
will be carried out soon, with an investment of 14 million
Egyptian pounds (4.1 million U.S. dollars) and 1 million dollars
donated by the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization.
</P>
<P>
Engineer Hassan Shahti, the official in charge of the project,
said Monday that the new phase will last five years from 1999 to
2004, the Arabic Alam Al Yom newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It envisages the construction of 300 houses for bedouins, the
reclamation of 600 feddans (252 hectares) in central Sinai, and
the distribution of food among bedouins at 15 percent of the
market price.
</P>
<P>
The first and second phases, which began in 1986, had been
completed at a total cost of about 75 million pounds (22 million
dollars) for the building of houses for bedouins and the
construction of water dams and outlets in the region.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The third international exhibition of furniture and
internal design will be held in Cairo during the first week of
September.
</P>
<P>
The show in the Cairo International Conference Center on
September 2-5 will group together manufacturers of furniture in
Egypt, the Alam Al Yom said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The organizing company Chairman Mohsin Ghozzi said Monday that
the exhibition would display local and imported furniture for
bathroom, bedroom, garden, swimming pool as well as hotel and
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that 130 companies will take part in the
exhibition and no less than 25,000 people from Egypt, other Middle
East countries and Africa will visit the show.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Speaker of Yemeni Consultative Council Abdul Aziz
Abdul Ghani has said the Yemeni economic reforms have helped bring
the foreign debts down to 4.76 billion dollars by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at Sunday's Council meeting, he said Yemen's
external debts in 1994 reached 9.013 billion dollars, the Alam Al
Yom said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Council began its session Sunday to discuss
the issue of loans, assistance and development.
</P>
<P>
TRIPOLI -- Libya will host an international conference on
subterranean water reservoirs in drought areas on November 20-24
to seek proper means to preserve water in such areas.
</P>
<P>
The conference, jointly organized by the Libyan Ministry of
Agriculture and U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization is also designed to explore sound managing methods
and policies and review environmental impacts on the exploitation
of such reservoirs, the Alam Al Yom reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be attended by officials, experts and
specialists in this field from various continents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
