<HEADLINE> Euthanasia Not Punishable in Netherlands: Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Euthanasia, or requested
assistance with suicide, may become not punishable in the
Netherlands as the country considered to change its law concerning
the act.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Justice Minister Benk Korthais and Health Minister Els
Borst tabled on Tuesday to the lower house of the parliament a
proposal to exempt the act from criminal law, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
When approved by the legislators, a new provision will be added
to the Dutch Criminal Code to exempt the termination of life on
request and assistance with suicide if two conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
The two conditions under which a doctor will not be liable to
criminal prosecution are: he or she must have fulfilled the
requirements of due care as laid down in a separate act, the
Termination of Life on Request and Assistance with Suicide Act and
he or she must notify his or her actions to the municipal coroner
in accordance with the relevant provisions of the Burial and
Cremation Act.
</P>
<P>
But government officials warned that the two conditions are
important and that the general proposition that euthanasia and
assistance with suicide are no longer punishable offenses is not a
correct representation of the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
Regional review committees will continue to exist, however, to
review as before whether the conditions of due care have been met
in terminating life on request and assisting with suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
