<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Embassy Presents "White Book" on NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Embassy to Zambia
presented here Tuesday a "White Book" on crimes committed by NATO
during the first month of aggression against its country.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the book to the press, Yugoslav Charge d'Affaires
Dusan Zupan said Serbian and Yugoslav authorities have been
fighting the Albanian separatist guerrillas and terrorists who
killed not only the Serbs but also their fellow Albanians loyal to
the Yugoslav state.
</P>
<P>
"NATO planes struck targets several hundred kilometers away
from Kosovo, and all these targets were civilian: bridges,
refineries, houses, schools, hospitals, heating plants, power
plants, even churches and monasteries. All these objects were
targeted deliberately, because of extremely high precision of very
sophisticated NATO weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO aggression provoked huge exodus of Albanian and Serbian
refugees from the region, he told the press.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav diplomat said NATO planes targeted and killed
refugees who decided to go back homes.
</P>
<P>
"At this very moment, despite the presence of more than 37,000
U.N. troops, we have around 170,000 Serb refugees, more than
30,000 Albanians and several thousand Roma and refugees of other
nationalities out from Kosovo, due to the terror conducted by
Albanian separatists," he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO aggression has not solved anything in the Yugoslav
province but brought more violence, confusion and uncertainty
about the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is prepared to pay any price to keep its territorial
 integrity. "From the beginning, we maintained that political
solution is the only way and violence is not a civilized manner to
solve problems," the charge d'affairs said. 
</P>
