<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Eclipse Counting Down, Germans Prepare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- One day before this century's last
total eclipse that encounters their long and happy summer holiday,
millions of Germans are traveling towards the south and southwest,
eagerly waiting for the two-minute highlights when the sunshine
will totally overshadowed by the moon.
</P>
<P>
As astronomers have predicted, in a belt cutting through Europe
the total eclipse can be witnessed at Wednesday noon. The belt,
beginning from southeast Britain and ending at the Black See,
covers two German states, Baden-Wuertenburg in the southwest and
Bavaria in the south.
</P>
<P>
Just at the middle of the belt, two large cities, Munich and
Stuttgart, are recommended as the best sites to observe the
"Sofi," a nick abbreviation that Germans have invented to call the
eclipse.
</P>
<P>
Traffic volumes on highways leading to the two cities have
broken the historic records in recent days as millions
holiday-makers are hurrying there.
</P>
<P>
In Munich, a city which attracts thousands of tourists even in
common years, more than 200,000 eclipse observers are expected.
And a hot rock'n roll festival is due to begin Wednesday morning
at the city's Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Seats in a rotating restaurant in Munich, which will provide
special "Sofi Lunch" on the eclipse day and where observers can
have a sharp view on the black sun, were fully booked one month
ago. Expected customers to the restaurant include Roman Herzog,
former German president.
</P>
<P>
A more exciting scene is expected in Stuttgart, an industrial
metropolitan well known as the headquarters of German automotive
giant Daimler-Chrysler. The city announces that it will welcome
some 500,000 visitors, many of whom come from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
And none Mercedes car will be produced in Daimler-Chrysler's
Stuttgart factory Wednesday since the company has planned a halt
of its manufacture line to let its staff take part in the eclipse
revelry.
</P>
<P>
In cities where only part of eclipse can be seen, Germans'
enthusiasm is still kept high.
</P>
<P>
The capital Berlin, the northern harbor of Hamburg, and dozens
of cities and towns are reportedly preparing "Sofi Festivals."
Some of them have planned to hold rallies in medieval style.
Special glasses for eclipse observation are sold in all kinds of
stores and highway gas stations.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to the carnival atmosphere, German media are due to
pay vast coverage over the eclipse. Leading television networks
such as ARD and RTL have planned live reportages on the entire
process with cameras on board an observation plane. Newspapers,
from the conservative "Die Welt" to the tabloid "Bild," depict the
coming "Sofi" with cover stories or special editions.
</P>
<P>
Expecting a total darkness to shadow the country for minutes
Wednesday, German authorities have been prepared for traffic jams
or disasters on highways.
</P>
<P>
But of course, everything depends on the weather. On Tuesday,
German Weather Service forecast cloud or shower would occur in
most part of the country, and in Munich, the possibility of a
sunny day would be no higher than 20 percent. It is afraid that
German and foreign visitors can do nothing more than watch the
eclipse on TV in their rooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Internet Security Software Market Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide market for
Internet security software jumped 43 percent over 1997 and reached
3.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, a U.S. market research firm said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This year, according to International Data Corporation (IDC),
the market will jump another 39 percent to 4.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the United States was the largest regional market for
Internet security software, representing 54 percent of the market.
Western Europe presents the next-largest opportunity, with 28
percent of the market share.
</P>
<P>
IDC expects the market to continue to expand. By 2001, the
market will have more than double its 1998 value. By 2003,
revenues will approach 8.3 billion dollars, representing a solid
21 percent compound annual growth rate from 1998.
</P>
<P>
IDC splits the Internet security software market into four
segments: firewall, encryption, antiviral, and authentication,
authorization and administration software.
</P>
<P>
Authentication, authorization and administration products
represented the largest segment in the 1998 market with 1.6
billion dollars, IDC said. This segment will maintain its top spot
through 2003, when its worth will exceed 3.7 billion dollars.
Firewalls are a fast-growing segment. From 1997 to 1998, the value
of this segment increased 80 percent to 442 million dollars. By
2003, its revenues will approach 1.5 billion dollars. The
increasing popularity of e-commerce is contributing to the growth
of firewalls, IDC said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spice Girls Creator Killed in Car Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Bob Herbert, the man who
originally put together the British pop supergroup the Spice
Girls, has died in a car accident, the record company RCA said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Herbert, 57, who picked the five young English women after they
answered his ad in the Stage magazine, was killed instantly Monday
when his car crashed in heavy rain, RCA said.
</P>
<P>
Police said the accident happened on the main road through
Windsor Great Park, Berkshire.
</P>
<P>
Herbert, who was driving a red MGF sports car, lost control in
heavy rain. The car spun and was struck by another car, forcing
the vehicle to leave the carriageway and to collide with a wooden
fence.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old man driving the other car suffered chest
injures which were not serious.
</P>
<P>
The Spice Girls were "shocked and saddened" by the news of his
death, a spokeswoman for the group said.
</P>
<P>
Herbert was the current manager of the British pop boy band
Five. 
