<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Likely to Issue Resolution on Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming summit of the
Southern African Development Community slated for August 18 is
likely to issue a resolution on military support to the Angolan
government in its fight against the rebel UNITA movement.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaure Mbuende told a press conference
here Tuesday that all SADC members agreed that they should do
something to support the unarmed Angolan people, especially women
and children in this fighting launched by Jonas Savimbi, the
Mozambique News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"A resolution is on the way to focus on what could be done for
the Angolan government which includes possible military support,"
he said. Mbuende said there is now no reason for Angolan
government to hold peaceful negotiations with Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Savimbi's friends in Africa, Europe or other
places should tell Savimbi that there is no excuse for the
existence in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"They should ask him to give up war instead of continuing to
supply him with advanced weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende believes that there is no sign showing Savimbi is
willing to end the war, since he not only continues purposefully
sabotaging the peace accord signed with the government, but also
concern himself with the purchase of more weapons including
advanced ones.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also discuss the conflict in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) and be briefed on the geo-political
military situation in Caprivi, Namibia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the annual summit will discuss financial and
economic issues, especially issues concerning food security.
</P>
