<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- London stocks tumbled more than 2
percent to a six-month low Tuesday as the share sell-off on both
sides of the Atlantic continued.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 closed 148 points lower at 5978.4, a fall of 2.4
percent - below the trough of its recent trade range and its
lowest closing level since February 12.
</P>
<P>
The index ended the session 10.3 percent below its lifetime
peak set in May as financial and growth stocks took some of the
heaviest hits.
</P>
<P>
The recent rise in bond yields on both sides of the Atlantic
sparked sharp selling of UK stocks, traders said, with telecoms
and banks the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Telewest Communications closed down 20.75p, or 8.8 percent at
216.5p. Cable and Wireless gave up 5.72 percent - contributing to
the 37 points that telecom stocks erased from the blue chip index.
</P>
<P>
Among financials, Standard Chartered lost 73p, or 8.3 percent,
at 806p, while Royal Bank of Scotland shed 86p, or 7 percent, at
1135p.
</P>
<P>
Germany's DAX index fell well over 1 percent on the day as
concerns of a possible interest rate hike in the United States and
Europe continued to dog the market.
</P>
<P>
The DAX ended down 86.43 points, or 1.7 percent, at 5000.87,
losing most of the ground picked up during a two-day rebound.
</P>
<P>
Leading French stocks ended the day down more than 1 percent.
The CAC-40 blue-chip index ended off 1.11 percent at 4245.35
points.  
</P>
