<HEADLINE> Oil Price Surge Puts Pressure On Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- A record surge in the oil price
last month sent the cost of raw materials rising at its fastest
rate for almost 20 years in Britain, according to latest official
figures.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said oil prices rose by 21.8
percent in July, helping to take producer input prices up a
seasonally adjusted 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was the highest monthly rate of producer input price
inflation since January 1980, and was almost double expectations.
</P>
<P>
Despite the surge in raw material costs, factory gate prices
remained little changed, suggesting manufacturers were absorbing
increased costs into margins.
</P>
<P>
Output prices rose by a non-seasonally adjusted 0.2 percent in
July to leave annual inflation at 1.1 percent, in line with City
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
"The output side of the figures was much more in line with what
the markets expected," said Jeremy Hawkins, economist at Bank of
America.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that manufacturers are weathering rising oil
prices by cutting labor costs.
</P>
<P>
"Raw material costs are just one element in costs, and their
pick-up is so far likely to have limited inflationary
consequences," an analyst said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
