<HEADLINE> Kenya Not to Default on Foreign Debt: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Ministry said
Tuesday that the country would not default on external debts
despite its delay in paying some debts.
</P>
<P>
"There has been some slippage in service payments, a delay of
one or two weeks, but not defaulting on debt. We are not about to
default, that is too strong a word," Masakhalia said.
</P>
<P>
Large amounts of debt was maturing this year and Kenya is
required to use a lot of foreign currency to meet its
obligations, said Masakhalia.
</P>
<P>
Kenya encountered lags in available revenue to convert to
foreign currency, but the minister said the government would not
borrow extensively from domestic markets to meet their obligations
due to the pursuit of a balanced budgetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Micah Cheserem, governor of Central Bank of Kenya, said the
central bank had enough dollars to meet the country's debt
obligations.
</P>
<P>
"To say we are defaulting is not accurate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency reserves held by Kenya's banking system stood
at 946 million U.S. dollars at the end of May. The figure for
official foreign currency reserves held by the central bank was
619 million dollars by late May.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had external debt of some 4.4 billion dollars in May,
treasury and central bank figures showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
