<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Pool Resources for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Foreign Minister
Jakaya Kikwete Tuesday called on African countries to integrate
their resources so that they could compete effectively in the
world in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing students of the East African Uongozi (Leadership)
Institute in the northern town of Arusha, Kikwete said cooperation
is key to the continent's survival, particularly when economic
globalization has become an irreversible trend of the world.
</P>
<P>
African countries should draw experience from other parts of
the world in forming economic groupings like the European Union,
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), he said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Africa is pushing ahead with the agenda of economic
integration, he said, adding that the process of building the
African Economic Community has started as various countries have
formed regional groupings and are negotiating crucial protocols on
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kikwete criticized the Western media, which
constantly portrays negative sides of the continent, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
He said although Africa is still rife with conflicts for
decades, it has made great efforts in bringing them to an end
through peaceful resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is stigmatized collectively," Kikwete said during a
working tour to the college where students come from various
African, American and European countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Africa is not entirely in war or conflicts. The
Uongozi Institute's main goal is to foster leadership qualities of
the younger generation of east Africans. The students are
undergoing a joint program of four universities from Tanzania,
Kenya, Uganda and the United States. 
</P>
