<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Release of Hostages in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday voiced his relief that all United Nations and
West African peacekeepers had been released by a group of Sierra
Leonean rebels and called on all parties concerned to ensure there
was no repetition.
</P>
<P>
"With the resolution of this deplorable episode, all Sierra
Leoneans and the international community should now look ahead and
devote all energies to the implementation of the Lome Peace
Agreement," Annan said in a statement issued here through his
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an accord signed in Lome, the Togolese
capital on July 7 aimed at ending an eight-year civil war in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks were in reaction to the release by rebels of
the last group of military and civilian hostages held for the past
week in the West African jungle.
</P>
<P>
They included about 200 civilians, 20 Nigerians from a West
African peacekeeping force, and a U.N. military observer. Other
hostages had been set free earlier.
</P>
<P>
The release ended a crisis triggered by the seizure last
week of about 40 foreigners who had set out to secure the
release of the Sierra Leone civilians, including a large number
of children.
</P>
<P>
Annan gratefully acknowledged the "crucial role" played by
the Sierra Leone government and president, as well as other
regional leaders and the former rebel Revolutionary United
Front led by Foday Sankoh, in seeking a peaceful resolution of
of the situation. 
</P>
