<HEADLINE> Cattle-rustling Causes Famine in E. Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Cattle rustling and banditry
have disrupted normal agricultural activities and resulted in a
food shortage in Kenya's Eastern Province, a member of parliament
Tuesday told a workshop facilitated by Kenyan Agriculture
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of residents in the province experienced
cattle rustling or banditry, making it difficult for them to
concentrate on farming, said legislator Maoka Maore.
</P>
<P>
Maore revealed that out of the 13 districts in the province,
only three districts were free of banditry and cattle-rustling.
</P>
<P>
He said livestock farmers in the province had lost thousands of
cattle to rustlers and most of the victims never recover their
livestock.
</P>
<P>
Maore said rampant banditry had scared some residents off their
home, making it difficult to engage in meaningful economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
The two-day workshop brought together stakeholders in the food
 production industry in Eastern Province, with an aim to formulate
a sound national food policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
