<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Stop Airstrikes on Iraq on Wednesday Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States would not
stop hitting Iraqi military sites despite Wednesday's eclipse of
the sun, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. and British
warplanes patrolling no-fly zones in northern and southern Iraq
would continue their attacks on Iraqi military sites when
encourtering challenges from Iraq's defense system.
</P>
<P>
He was answering a reporter's question whether the U.S. and
British military would suspend airstrikes to avoid hitting Iraqis
who might be out in the open watching the eclipse, which includes
Turkey, Iran, Iraq and Pakistan in its sweep.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't challenge the allied planes, the allied planes
will not respond," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. warplanes had been striking Iraqi military sites
on the average of 15 time a month in the eight months since
Operation Desert Fox last December, about six a month in the
southern no-fly zone and nine a month in the northern one.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, U.S. warplanes attacked Iraqi military sites in a
second consecutive day of bombings in the northern no-fly zone,
according to U.S. European Command based in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Air Force F-15s and F-16s dropped precision-guided bombs on two
separate communications facilities, north and northeast of Mosul,
the command said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Bacon also reporter U.S airstrikes in the southern no-fly zone
but provided no details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
