<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) commended Tuesday the authorities of the Philippines
for the sustained implementation of economic policies under the
program that had allowed the southeast Asian country to weather
the regional crisis relatively well.
</P>
<P>
In an annual review of the Philippine economy, the IMF noted
that the country's "external position had improved markedly,
economic growth has started to recover, and inflation had come
down well within program targets."
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF said, the country still has to meet the twin
challenge of preserving the stabilization gains while bolstering
the prospects for a strong and sustained recovery.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the countries most heavily affected by the Asian
financial crisis, the Philippine economy was able to avoid a
severe recession and the disruptions to economic activity
experienced elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Following a 5 percent growth of the gross domestic product
(GDP) in 1997, the economy contracted slightly by 0.5 percent in
1998. For the year of 1999, GDP growth is projected in a range of
1-3 percent, with recent developments suggesting an outcome in the
upper half of the range.  
