<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Outlines U.N. Post-Ballot Role in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan proposed on Tuesday that the United Nations should play
"a substative role" in East Timor in the post-ballot period with
its increasing presence there.
</P>
<P>
In his new report to the Security Council, Annan said
irrespective of the outcome of the August 30 vote on the future of
the territory, the U.N. has to redouble its efforts to build
confidence and support stability in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The report proposes that the U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) established on June 11 be restructed for the interim
phase, with an eventual number of 460 civilian police, up from 280
proposed before.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET military component would be increased to 300 from 50 to
liaise the Indonesian armed forces and different political forces
in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The military component would be also charged with advising on
security matters including the disarmament of local militias.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes in UNAMET will ensure the presence of the
U.N. in all 13 districts of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General has requested authorization for an
initial period of three months for UNAMET presence from the date
of the ballot. He had previously decided that UNAMET stay until
September 30, one month from the voting date.
</P>
<P>
Based on the May 5 agreement signed by Indonesia, Portugal and
the U.N., the world body will organize and conduct a popular
consultation to determine the future of East Timor, former
Portuguese colony occupied by Indonesia in 1975.
</P>
<P>
If the majority of the 800,000 East Timorese accept a special
autonomy formula, the U.N. is requested to monitor and verify the
implementation of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
If the result is a rejection of autonomy, arrangements will be
made for the peaceful transfer of authority in East Timor to the
U.N. which will initiate the procedure for the territory to go
towards independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Economy in Cautious Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The UK economy is showing clear
signs of recovery, according to new figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Confidence in the manufacturing industry has improved for the
first time in 18 months, and High Street or consumer spending rose
for the second month in a row. However, both sectors say
conditions are still tough, and warn that an increase in interest
rates could have an adverse effect.
</P>
<P>
The survey of manufacturers for the Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) shows an upbeat mood in all the UK's key regions.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since the start of 1998, more manufacturers
were optimistic than pessimistic, though companies were still
reporting falling output and orders.
</P>
<P>
"While many regions seem poised to emerge from the
manufacturing recession, the rises in confidence in some regions
should be treated with caution," BBC quoted Sudhir Junankar of the
CBI as saying. "Manufacturers across the UK are facing a
relentless squeeze on profit margins and are struggling to cope
with a strong pound."
</P>
<P>
The CBI report came after the government's July survey of UK
purchasing managers showed manufacturing growing at its fastest
rate for 18 months. However, the fragility of the recovery is
illustrated by the fact that the latest official figures showed
factory output was falling.
</P>
<P>
And a study released this week predicted that 160,000 factory
jobs could be lost over the next 18 months because of the strong
pound.
</P>
<P>
On High Street, shop sales grew by 0.8 percent in July, fueled
by the effects of seasonal items, from ice-cream to garden
furniture.
</P>
<P>
The figures, from the British Retail Consortium (BRC), followed
June's even bigger growth of 1.8 percent. However, the BRC said
the continuing rise in sales was being achieved at a price.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Higginson, chairman of the BRC's economic affairs
committee, said, "There appears to be the beginnings of a recovery
in sales, but we are far from the boom conditions that some people
are suggesting, judged by the performance of the housing market."
</P>
<P>
These latest sets of figures come against the backdrop of a
report by the Society of Business Economists (SBE) which saw the
outlook for the UK economy brightening.
</P>
<P>
It said consumer spending was set to rise and exporters'
prospects were improving, boosted by recent interest rate cuts and
strong house price growth.
</P>
<P>
The SBE's chairman, David Kern, said that as the UK had
successfully avoided a recession, its economy was set to return to
trend growth by the second half of this financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
