<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall In Third Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks suffered
more losses for the third straight day Tuesday as investors widely
expected the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones closed down 52.55 at 10,655.15. The blue chip
index fell 554.69 points or 4.9 percent from its record closing
high of 11,209.84 set on July 16.
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned two weeks ago
that the Federal would raise interest rates to preempt inflation
from the U.S. economy if the new data showed pressures on
inflation. The market took a nosedive after the warning.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve is widely expected to raise interest rates
on August 24 when it meets on the monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 16.37 at 1,281.43, and the technology heavy Nasdaq
index fell 28.87 at 2,490.11, about 13 percent below its record
high.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 7.09 at 603.37 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 7.10 at 770.77. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.07 at 422.82.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,307 down, 788 up and 461
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 831.64 million shares from 674.62
million in the previous session. 
</P>
