<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Set to Vaccinate 10 Million Children in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- United Nations agencies
are preparing to vaccinate some 10 million children against polio
in the Democratic Republic of Congo, which has one of the highest
virus transmission rates in the world, the U.N. officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central African country's warring parties have agreed to
stop fighting so the first of three vaccination required to ensure
effective immunization can begin this weekend, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who had appealed for "Days
of Tranquillity" to allow the immunization program to go ahead, has
received assurances from the country that they would lay down
their weapons.
</P>
<P>
Even with localized fighting, relief agencies believe the
campaign can reach more than 95 percent of children under five
years of age.
</P>
<P>
In his call for the parties to comply with the truce to
facilitate the polio immunization campaign, Annan said the
vaccination campaigns were "a platform for the peace-building
process. They open windows of opportunity for dialogue between the
different sides."
</P>
<P>
The campaign to eradicate polio from the world by the end of
they year 2000 is being spearheaded by the World Health
Organization (WHO) and the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF). Congo (K) is the single highest priority in the global
polio eradication effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
