<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Witnesses Millennium's Last Solar Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- As the moon briefly blocked
the rays of the setting sun over large parts of central India
Wednesday evening, millions of Indians caught the last chance in
the millennium to watch the nature's grand cosmic drama.
</P>
<P>
A ribbon of darkness girdled central parts of the country,
where sunlight was totally blotted out by the moon, while people
elsewhere including the Indian capital could only witness a
partial eclipse, that brought in early twilight in a sky already
darkened by the clouds.
</P>
<P>
As the eclipse swept across India, the air chilled, an anxious
silence fell, confused birds headed home and flowers folded their
petals before the sun reappeared and made a final bow out of the
horizon later.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers here said the eclipse started in the Atlantic in
Canada at sunrise, swept through Cornwall in southwest Britain,
across Europe through northern France, Germany, Austria, Hungary
and Romania, then through Iran and Iraq in west Asia and in
neighboring Pakistan before entering India.
</P>
<P>
It was first visible over India's western coast at 17:58 p.m.
local time. The moon's shadow raced across central India to the
Bay of Bengal at 18:06 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon of nature lasted a little over a minute in some
parts of the country and barely 25 seconds in other areas, but it
created an 80-kilometer-wide corridor of darkness across central
India.
</P>
<P>
However, the breathtaking sights typical of a solar eclipse
were missing for Indians this time.
</P>
<P>
Keeping in mind the sunset time of the eclipse and rainy
forecasts, several Indian astrophysicists headed to Iran, which
offered a better view to conduct experiments.
</P>
<P>
People in New Delhi missed the spectacle as the capital did not
fall in the line of totality. A partial eclipse started in the
city at 16:51 p.m. local time and lasted for about two hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
