<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 616 Zimbabwean Families to Be Settled Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A total of 616 families will have
been resettled on 15 of the acquired farms by the end of this
month, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"More people will be resettled on about 54,000 hectares of land
on the remaining 23 farms that have been acquired," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The president said this at the commemoration of the Heroes Day
at the National Heroes Acre in capital Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said the second phase of the land reform program had now
gathered momentum and that the government had endorsed the
inception phase framework plan, thus sanctioning its
implementation with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the governments of Norway, Sweden, the Netherlands
and the United States had committed one million U.S. dollars for
the establishment of a technical support unit to facilitate the
implementation phase.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the land reform program would provide a sustainable
base upon which to predicate long-term peace, political stability
and favorable prospects for sustainable economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The government's aim has always been to acquire at least one
million hectares of commercial farm land every year for
resettlement purposes in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The government has acquired 38 farms so far this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 559 families were resettled last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
