<HEADLINE> Angolan Situation Comes into U.S. Public Notice: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Luanda, August 11 (xinhua) -- Actual situation in Angola has
been brought into public notice in the United States by newspapers
and televisions, an official with the Angolan Foreign Ministry
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said that among other issues, the U.S. press has
made salient the recently issued warrant for the capture of Jonas
Savimbi, head of the rebellious National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), who was accused by the police of
leading the armed anti-humanity rebellion.
</P>
<P>
U.S. press also noticed that Robert Fowler, Chairman of the
U.N. Committee of Sanctions, had made an appeal to international
intelligence agencies and the International Police (Interpol) for
placing embargoes against UNITA on arms and diamonds, said the
unidentified foreign ministry official.
</P>
<P>
He added that U.S. newspapers pointed out that the U.S. shared
with U.N. intelligence and information when they tried to identify
those who violated the sanctions against the UNITA. 
