<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Premiers Agree on Deep Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada's provincial premiers and
territorial leaders reached a consensus here Tuesday to make deep
tax cuts due to an anticipated surplus in the next federal budget.
</P>
<P>
During the country's 40th conference of provincial premiers,
slated from Monday to Wednesday, the local leaders agreed that
Ottawa should use the impending surplus of 10 billion Canadian
dollars (6.8 billion U.S. dollars) to make deep tax cuts and
restore transfer payments to the provinces.
</P>
<P>
Conference Host Lucien Bouchard of Quebec hailed the agreement
as a "balanced approach," saying that "reducing taxes will improve
the Canadian economy, accelerate job growth, and alleviate the
heavy fiscal burden taxpayers are shouldering."
</P>
<P>
The Royal Bank of Canada, the biggest private-run bank in the
country, suggested during the third day of the meeting, a 20
percent tax cut over five years, saying Ottawa would be able to do
it without making spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
In a study to be released Wednesday, the bank says the budget
surplus could reach 25.9 billion Canadian dollars (about 17.7
billion dollars) by the fiscal year 2004-2005.
</P>
<P>
Even if Ottawa set aside 7 billion Canadian dollars (about 4.8
billion dollars) as a cushion, it would still have an 18.9 billion
Canadian dollar (about 12.9 billion dollars) fiscal windfall for
tax cuts, the study says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
