<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation Remains Tense in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Ambon, capital
of Indonesia's Maluku province, remained tense till Wednesday
afternoon as clashes continued to claim lives.
</P>
<P>
Three people died and 56 others were wounded Wednesday,
according to the Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Military Command Chief Brigadier General Max Tamaela
denied reports that security forces had clashed in Ambon.
</P>
<P>
Rumors about the conflict appeared after shots were heard
during rioting. After checks were made it was found that some
people had worn security forces' uniforms during the incident,
Tamaela said.
</P>
<P>
They have deliberately used the uniform to split the security
forces, he said, adding that he had seized some of them.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, military spokesman Major General Syamsul Maarif
Wednesday said security authorities are investigating rumors that
a large number of illegal firearms have been sent into Ambon.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Col. Saleh Saaf also said that police were
investigating rumors about a container of firearms having been
smuggled into Ambon.
</P>
<P>
"Intelligence officers are still investigating the rumors but
so far no indication about their truth has been found," he said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that some rioters had used firearms but they were
all home-made.
</P>
<P>
Located about 2,300 kilometers east of Jakarta, Ambon has been
rocked by religious unrest that has killed about 400 people this
year. Authorities said more than 400 have been injured since
religious clashes erupted in the province in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
In Ambon, about 60 percent of the population are Christian.
Most of the rest are Muslims, many of them immigrants from other
islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
