<HEADLINE> Israel Closes Palestinian Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel sealed off several
Palestinian villages in the West Bank Wednesday after an Israeli
man was moderately wounded in a shooting incident late Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers imposed a closure on areas close to the
village of Arabbe in northern West Bank, where a Jewish settler
was shot and wounded, Israel Radio reported. No organization
claimed responsibility for the incident yet.
</P>
<P>
Israelis were warned that there might be an increase in
militant attacks since Israel and the Palestinians were resuming
the peace process stalled under former Israeli prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance Movement, or Hamas, which opposes to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace making, has said that it would resume
militant attacks against Israel. It has carried out several major
suicide bombings in Israel since 1993, when the historic Oslo
accords between Israel and the Palestinians were signed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Police Chief Yehuda Wilk told Israeli army radio that
Israeli security forces had foiled several attack attempts in the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
A 23-year-old Palestinian from the West Bank town of Bethlehem
rammed his car twice into a group of Israeli soldiers Tuesday at
an intersection about 30 miles southwest of Jerusalem, injuring 11
before being shot to death by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
But the new Israeli government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) took careful steps
to avoid a confrontation after the terror attack.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian official said on condition of anonymity that
Barak and PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat will hold a summit after
negotiators from the two sides reach agreement on a timetable
for the implementation of the Wye accord signed last year.
</P>
<P>
Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat met in Jerusalem Wednesday afternoon to resume their
negotiations, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office on July 6, Barak has promised to carry out
the Wye agreement, but he proposed to fold the third and final
part, of the agreement into final-status talks, which deals with
thorny issues such as Jerusalem and settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have turned down the idea, calling on Barak to
fully implement the Wye before entering the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
During their second summit late last month since Barak
assuming office, Barak gave Arafat two weeks to consider his
propos, which ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media have reported that secret channels had been
established to work out the timetable of the implementation.
Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas, or Abu Mazen, told Palestinian
radio Wednesday that he was hopeful that agreement would be
reached on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides seemed to have agreed on the timetable to further
implement the last two stages of the Wye accord to hand over 11
percent more of the West Bank to the Palestinians. Israel had
returned 2 percent of the land in the first stage under the accord.
</P>
<P>
Barak has said he would resume troops withdrawal in early
September and Arafat has reluctantly accepted the starting
time.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides are still disputing over Barak's proposal to
delay the third stage until after a framework for the final-status
talks has been worked out, or around February next year.
</P>
<P>
Barak told a security cabinet meeting Wednesday that he would
implement the Wye agreement, but expected the PNA would consider
his proposal.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Haaret said Barak was now offering to carry out
the final part of the Wye accord by January. Sher was to propose
the idea to Erekat when they met, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
But Abu Mazen reportedly told Barak during a secret meeting
earlier this week that the implementation of Wye should be
completed in full by mid-November in line with its original
timetable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
