<HEADLINE> China Attaches Importance to Protection of Ethnic Minorities' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- the Chinese government has
attached great importance to protecting the rights of the country'
s 55 ethnic minorities over the past 50 years, said a senior
Chinese official here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"China is a unified nation with many ethnic groups," said Qiao
Zonghuai, head of the Chinese Observer Delegation, during the 51st
session of a United Nations sub-commission on the promotion and
protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
To maintain and develop relations of equality, unity and mutual
assistance among all ethnic groups, and to prohibit ethnic hatred
and discrimination, Qiao said the Chinese government has
formulated and implemented a series of effective policies, such as
the system of ethnic autonomy,
</P>
<P>
On the elimination of racial discrimination, he told the
meeting that "with great help from the central government, arduous
efforts by the ethnic people have substantially changed the
situation in ethnic regions, hence the enjoyment of human rights
by ethnic peoples has been remarkably improved."
</P>
<P>
The population of the 55 minority groups amounts to 108 million,
which accounts for 8.98% of the total population of China.
</P>
<P>
Qiao also told the meeting that his delegation fully endorses
the World Conference Against Racism and Racial Discrimination in
2001, which is now under preparation by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the parties concerned can reach an agreement on such
substantive matters as the function and agenda of the conference
and thus start the overall preparatory process," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
