the Russian republics of Chechnya and Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
Four people were reportedly killed in the bombing by
unidentified planes in Zemo Omalo, Georgia, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Following strong protests by Georgian leaders, who allege the
planes were Russian, Moscow has agreed to set up a Russian-
Georgian commission to investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
After a joint session of the commission Wednesday morning,
chaired by Georgia's Chief of General Staff Dzhoni
Pirskhalaishvili, investigators set out for Zemo Omalo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Georgian State Security Ministry said it has
initiated criminal proceedings over the incident.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted eyewitnesses as saying the planes appeared to
be coming from the direction of Dagestan and dropped about 3,000
plastic cluster bombs and flew north.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov assured Georgian State
Minister Vazha Lordkipanidze Tuesday that if evidence is found
that confirms the bombs were dropped by Russian planes, Russia
will officially apologize to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry has rejected the charges brought
against its air force. 
</P>
