My Life that he was summoned to a meeting with United chairman
Martin Edwards and plc chairman Sir Roland Smith.
</P>
<P>
Sir Alex felt the meeting had been set up to discuss his then
number two Brian Kidd whom, the manager felt, had been undermining
his authority. The purchase of Dwight Yorke was also expected to
be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
"I was under the impression the purpose of our gathering was to
discuss Kidd and Yorke, but Martin Edwards began with a long
speech about me," writes Ferguson. "He praised my capacities as a
manager but said my success at Old Trafford had made me a
celebrity and I was not focusing on the job as much as I had done.
"
</P>
<P>
He adds: "My new found interest in owning racehorses had
obviously not gone down well. I could hardly believe what I was
hearing but let Martin and Sir Roland make their points before
asking 'Do you want me to call it a day?
</P>
<P>
"'No, no,' they both said quickly, adding further tributes to
my management and insisting they were only trying to give me
advice."
</P>
<P>
Ferguson replied: "Don't you realise the only way I can survive
is to have a release from football?" 
