<HEADLINE> Canada Warns of Cutting Radarsat-2 Connection with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Industry Minister John
Manley has threatened to cut the American connection with the
Canadian Radarsat-2 satellite project if the U.S. continues to
hamper the project with delays.
</P>
<P>
Canadian media "the Globe and Mail" and "the Ottawa Citizen"
Wednesday quoted Manley as complaining about delayed permission by
the U.S. to export key hardware to Canada for the 305-million-
dollar (about 207 million U.S. dollars) satellite, which is
scheduled to be launched in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The project has been unable for eight months to get the U.S.
government permission to export the satellite shell "bus" to
Canada, or to even allow the American parent company to work with
its Canadian subsidiary on the project, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say they are concerned that data from Radarsat-2,
which can provide images as small as three meters through darkness
or clouds, could be acquired by potential enemies, the newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
Manley told an international aerospace conference Tuesday that
although Ottawa is still trying to resolve the issue with
Washington, his country will look for a European company to supply
the commercial satellite "bus." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
