<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Working to Prevent Revenue Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa or COMESA is working out ways of preventing
revenue losses that might arise when the regional grouping enters
a free trade area scheduled for October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony for the grant of 16 million
U.S. dollars given by the European Union (EU) to the COMESA here
Wednesday, Secretary-General of the African regional organization
Erastus Mwencha noted that the grant, which will go to a project
on the harmonization of customs and trade statistics, has come at
a critical time when COMESA members are preparing to launch a free
trade area.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said that the COMESA has managed to harmonize customs
and trade statistics in 13 out of the 21 member countries.
</P>
<P>
"My appeal to member states is to remain on course as regards
liberalization and integration of our economics in the full
assurance that the benefits of the free trade area will definitely
outweigh the transition costs," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, EU resident representative
Jochen Krebs said that his organization is happy with the efforts
the COMESA is making in creating a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Krebs also pledged EU's continued support for the COMESA
project on harmonization of customs and trade statistics.
</P>
<P>
The EU official noted that an improved customs system will make
it easier for COMESA countries to trade with each other. 
</P>
