<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Residents View Eclipse With Mixed Feelings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Belgium viewed the
eclipse Wednesday with mixed feelings. Some managed to get a
glimpse of the rare phenomenon at a few vantage points, while
others chose to view it at home and on television. Others were
caught in traffic jams on highways and were not able to reach an
advantageous location to see it.
</P>
<P>
Dark clouds and continuous drizzle overnight from Monday to
Tuesday kept many eclipse watchers at home until early Wednesday
morning when the weather appeared as if it might clear.
</P>
<P>
The sudden rush toward the south of the country or into the
north of neighboring France caused heavy traffic congestion on the
highways, especially in southern Belgium, where highways and
national roads were reportedly packed with cars. Police reports
estimated around 70,000 cars were on the road.
</P>
<P>
Those who had arrived at points of advantage in southern
Belgium before Wednesday had to demonstrate great patience before
they could finally catch a glimpse of the solar eclipse through
cloud openings.
</P>
<P>
When the clouds would part and they could see the eclipse
occurring, they would cheer loudly.
</P>
<P>
A solar eclipse happens when the moon passes directly between
the sun and the earth, blocking the light from the sun.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's solar eclipse is estimated to be visible in whole
or in part to around 2 billion people worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
