<HEADLINE> Dhaka Asks U.N. to Reconsider Sending Back Bangladeshi Police Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has requested the
Untied Nations to review its decision of sending back the
country's police contingent from peace-keeping operations in
Kosovo, Yugoslavia, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our permanent representative at the U.N. headquarters has been
instructed to make appeal to U.N. Secretary-General (Kofi Annan)
to review the matter," Azad told reporters at a news briefing
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh sent 49 policemen, including senior officers, to
Kosovo late last month to take part in the peace-keeping
operations there, but only 13 had passed various tests. About 50
policemen from Nepal were also being sent back on similar grounds,
reports here said.
</P>
<P>
Azad said the country was officially informed about the
decision of the Department of Peace-Keeping Operations to
repatriate 36 of the 49 police officers "on grounds of failing the
requisite in-mission test conducted in English, driving and
firearm shooting."
</P>
<P>
Describing the incident as "unfortunate for all sides --
Bangladesh and the U.N.," the foreign minister said Bangladesh,
which has been contributing to U.N. peace-keeping operations since
the late 1980s, has earned both appreciation and honor.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to send back the police officers was not expected
since all formalities and conditions laid down by the U.N. were
fully observed," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
