<HEADLINE> Mine Attack Toll Rises to 11 in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- At least 11 policemen have been
killed and more than 15 wounded in a powerful land mine blast
Wednesday in eastern Sri Lanka, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place in the government-controlled town of
Batticaloa, 300 kilometers east of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) have set
off a remote-controlled device as a police bus was leaving
Batticaloa, where the surrounding countryside is under rebel
control, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the mine blast killed nine policemen and
injured 14 others. No civilians were hurt as many local shops were
closed for a Hindu festival.
</P>
<P>
The blast followed an escalation of bomb attacks in recent
weeks by the Tamil Tigers, who have been fighting a 16-year-old
war against the government to demand a homeland for Tamil minority
in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
Monday, a rebel suicide bomber killed a senior army officer
near Batticaloa, in the Varakai army camp where he was
distributing food to civilians.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, 13 special task force commandos were killed
in a suicide bomb attack in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
And at the end of July, a moderate Tamil lawmaker was killed in
a suicide bomb attack on his car in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities expressed fears Monday that there could be
more violent attacks, amid police reports that the LTTE rebels had
sent out 10 bombers on suicide missions to Colombo, focusing on
carefully selected targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
