<HEADLINE> Beijing Tidies Up Outdoor Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- With 50 days left before New
China's 50th anniversary celebrations, Beijing is stepping up the
face-lifting of roadside structures.
</P>
<P>
All untidy or randomly placed advertisements and billboards
along the roads will be removed by September 15, a municipal
government official said at a meeting today.
</P>
<P>
Fu Bainan, director of Beijing's administration committee, said
that the number of advertising companies has increased to more
than 3,000 since 1978, and the number of outdoor billboards
approved by the municipal government in the past decade has hit 5,
213.
</P>
<P>
But, outdoor advertisements have somewhat grown out of control
in recent years, with the number of illegally set up billboards
hitting 259 or even more, he added.
</P>
<P>
"This has not only hurt the capital's image as a political and
cultural center, but also affected its traditional grace as an
ancient city," Fu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Mayor Wang Guangtao said that the cleanup drive covers
outdoor advertising in any forms which are against the law and
regulations or lack government approval.
</P>
<P>
He said that focus will be put on the face-lifting of Chang'an
Avenue, two ring roads, roads leading to the capital airport, and
all super-highways in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
