<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Eclipse Spotted in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 11 (Xinhua) -- People in Kuwait witnessed a
solar eclipse Wednesday afternoon, the second astronomical
phenomenon of this kind spotted here since 1952.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse, the last of the 20th century, began over the Gulf
country at about 13:44 (1044 GMT) and climaxed over 90 percent at
about 15:05 (1205 GMT). It ended at around 16:16 (1316 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Before and during the eclipse, traffic on streets and highways
turned thin as people returned home earlier than normally
scheduled, as many of them were anxious to watch the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
While thousands of people flocked to Kuwait's Science Club,
where a huge observatory is located, to see the eclipse, many
others used special glasses for the rare natural event.
</P>
<P>
People who preferred to be indoors also could follow up on the
solar eclipse through the Kuwait TV Station, which broadcast live
the event.
</P>
<P>
A solar eclipse, a rare alignment between the sun, moon and
earth, occurs when the orbit of the moon slides its disk exactly
between the sun and the earth, casting a shadow across the face of
the Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
