<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches National Reading Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday launched
the National Reading Month to encourage reading among its citizens
and make reading a national passion.
</P>
<P>
"We want reading to be a national passion among all
Malaysians," Education Minister Najib Tun Razak was quoted by
Bernama news agency as saying in his launching speech.
</P>
<P>
The reading culture should be encouraged as there would have to
be 100-percent literacy rate when Malaysia achieves developed
status in 2020, he said.
</P>
<P>
Najib wanted families to set up their own mini-libraries at
home to encourage reading among family members, saying many
Malaysians were literate but were not interested in reading and
this was not in keeping with a progressive nation.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the move by the National Library of Malaysia to
promote reading and the setting up of home libraries.
</P>
<P>
Based on 1996 figures, 41 percent of Malaysian families had
mini libraries at home and the literacy rate for Malaysia was 93
percent while 87 percent did some form of reading, and this showed
that not all who were literate read, he said. 
</P>
