<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Solar Eclipse Witnessed in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A total solar eclipse was
witnessed Wednesday in southwest England, with a partial shadowing
of the sun seen across other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse, starting at round 11.11 am (1011 GMT), plunged
south-west England into total darkness for about two minutes.
</P>
<P>
An estimated two million people, who have packed into south
Devon and Cornwall, the only areas in England within the eclipse's
"path of totality," cheered from clifftops, grounds and beaches as
the sun was totally obscured by the moon.
</P>
<P>
In London, where the eclipse can been seen 97 percent, trials
were adjourned briefly to allow jurors to go outside and watch
while many companies throughout the country gave employees time
off.
</P>
<P>
Millions of people across Britain have been watching from
houses, gardens, parks and streets to see the "once in a lifetime"
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's total solar eclipse was the first since 1927
observed in mainland Britain and according to astronomers, the
next one won't appear until September 23, 2090.
</P>
<P>
From Britain, the 64-mile (103 km) band of totality is crossing
the English Channel and extend across Northern France, Germany,
Austria and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse's maximum duration of 2 minutes 27 seconds will be
seen in central Romania. Then it will race at about 2,400 kph
cross the Black Sea to Turkey, Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The last sightings will be in Iran, Pakistan and India and it
will be ended at sunset over the Bay of Bengal off India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
