<HEADLINE> Anhui Lifts State of Emergency in Flood Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The government of east China's
Anhui Province today declared an end to the 30-day state of
emergency along the Yangtze River that runs through the province.
</P>
<P>
The floodwater has receded and the water level of the Yangtze's
Anhui section has dropped below the danger mark, and the focus of
the current flood-control work in the province has been shifted to
preparation for fighting against unexpected rainstorms in August
and September.
</P>
<P>
Anhui suffered severe floods this summer, with the Yangtze's
water level of 17.93 meters topping the danger mark since July 1.
The province declared a state of emergency on July 20 to deal with
the rising Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to water-control efforts and flood prevention facilities
built by Anhui last year, no major disasters struck the province,
and its economic losses have been reduced, local sources said.
</P>
