<HEADLINE> Indonesian Currency Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The weakening of the Indonesian
rupiah, which dipped to 8,000 to the U.S. dollar Wednesday
morning, is totally unrealistic and will not last long, Bank
Indonesia (BI) Governor Sjahril Sabirin said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was closed at 7,700/7,800 per U.S. dollar in
Wednesday's trading.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think this would last long. I hope it will improve in
the next one or two days," Sabirin told reporters at the Merdeka
Palace here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin was at the palace for a meeting with President B.J.
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
He said that the weakening of the rupiah against the dollar was
the result of the worsening political situation in the country,
following the violence in Aceh and Maluku.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been mounting in the two provinces as clashes have
begun to spread.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the central bank would intervene in the market to
strengthen the rupiah, Sabirin said this is not yet necessary.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday, the rupiah fell 290 points as it closed at 7,330/7,350
in the interbank spot market here, following the alleged criminal
action in an interbank transaction between publicly listed Bank
Bali and the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA).
</P>
<P>
The two institutions, Bank Bali and IBRA, had allegedly
committed a criminal act which also involves a member of the
ruling Golkar Party's central executive board.
</P>
<P>
Bank Bali allegedly paid Golkar's Deputy Treasurer Setyo
Novanto and other businessmen related to Golkar some 550 billion
rupiah in commission for recovering 904.6 billion rupiah (133
million U.S. dollars) in interbank credits.
</P>
<P>
Habibie Wednesday pledged that the government will probe into
the scandal that rocked Bank Bali.
</P>
<P>
"The matter is being processed by (central bank) Bank Indonesia
Governor (Sjahril Sabirin) and Finance Minister (Bambang
Subianto). Let us wait," Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
On the weakening of the rupiah against the dollar, a private
bank dealer said the doubtful situation of Indonesian bank
restructuring efforts had prompted investors to buy U.S. dollars
in large amounts.
</P>
<P>
Investors have begun to feel uneasy and express doubts about
the government's seriousness in handling Indonesia's banking
problems, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
