<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laparoscopic Surgery in Infancy Successful in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of doctors from the
Chinese University of Hong Kong (CUHK) have successfully used the
laparoscopic technique to perform a 95-percent subtotal
pancreatectomy in a two-month old infant.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the world for such complicated and
technically demanding operation to be used in infancy, and it
establishes Hong Kong as a leading center in pediatric endoscopic
surgery, according to Chung Kwong Yeung, head of the Division of
Pediatric Surgery under the CUHK.
</P>
<P>
The infant has suffered with nesidioblastosis (excessive growth
of pancreatic islet cells) causing persistent low blood sugar, a
rare condition affecting neonates, and the normal neurological
development of the baby indicates that her brain has not suffered
from damage after the operation, Yeung told a press conference
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A baby with nesidioblastosis usually presents in the first few
days of life with symptoms of severe hypoglycemia including
lethargy, poor feeding, hypotonia and repeated seizures, and if
the condition is not properly treated, the patient will suffer
from serious brain damage and mental retardation, the doctor
explained.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Department of Surgery at the CUHK also said
that they have pioneered many laparoscopic surgeries in Hong Kong
since the late 1980s, including the introduction of the first
laparoscopic cholecystectomy in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Division of Pediatric Surgery applied minimally invasive
surgical techniques in many operations in infants and young
children since the early 1990s, and set up one of the world's
first pediatric endoscopic surgery centers, according to Yeung.
</P>
<P>
Yeung said that the minimally invasive techniques have been
shown to have distinct advantages over traditional open methods in
causing minimal surgical trauma, less post-operative pain and
wound complications, faster recovery as well as shorter hospital
stay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0148 </DOCNO>
