<HEADLINE> Groundbreaking for Hydro-Power Project in SW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a hydro-power
project has begun in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, a
relatively underdeveloped region in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Jointly invested by the local government of Jinxiu Yao
Autonomous County and a Hong Kong company, the power station is
being built on the upper Dishui River.
</P>
<P>
A survey has shown that the river has the potential to have a
generating capacity of 78,500 kw of hydro-power.
</P>
<P>
In the initial stage of construction, a river dam is being
built at a cost of 245 million yuan and will be completed in two
and half years, at which time a plant will be installed with three
generators, each with a 9,000 kw capacity. The plant is expected
to produce 87 million kwh annually.
</P>
<P>
The river dam will not only alleviate the bottleneck in the
region's power supply, but will also play an important role in
controlling flood and drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
