<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The volume of foreign currency reserves in the
Moroccan Central Bank stood at 56.5 billion dirhams (about 5.8
billion U.S. dollars) in early August, up by 34.6 percent over the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The volume, which for the first time exceeded the
50-billion-dirham (5.15 billion dollars) reserve ceiling, is
enough to cover imports of commodities and services for seven
months, said a statement by the Moroccan Ministry of Finance,
Commerce, Industry and Handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
The increase was attributed to license revenues from the
country's second mobile telephone network. The revenues were
estimated at 900 million dollars in hard currency.
</P>
<P>
Tourism revenues in the first seven months of this year stood
at 700 million dollars and private foreign investments amounted to
some 400 million dollars during the first six months of the year,
the Arab daily Al Hayat quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The reserves would enable the central bank to rectify the gap
in the foreign trade balance, particularly the rise in wheat and
crop purchases by some 400 million dollars due to drought.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states are expected
to make greater profits in the coming year by steadily
implementing the OPEC decision to cut oil production.
</P>
<P>
Their petroleum revenues are due to exceed 80 billion dollars,
though fears of a collapse of the agreement are still hovering, the
Arab daily Al Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts agree that the average price of the Brent crude oil
will exceed 18 dollars per barrel in the year 2000 if the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) continue to
uphold the balance in petroleum markets.
</P>
<P>
GCC states may tend to increase their oil production next year
once OPEC decides to lift the production ceiling in 2000 to meet
the growing international demand, said a Western petroleum expert.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the OPEC agreement on production cut might begin
collapsing as the international petroleum storages would start
drying up, thus, inciting some OPEC members to increase production
in order to make additional profits.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq's imports from the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
account for 30 percent of the country's total commodity imports,
the Arab economic daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The volume of UAE exports to Iraq, which is subjected to
international sanctions since 1990, stood at 2.5 million dollars
in 1995 and had since increased to 55 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sixty UAE companies will attend the November international fair
in Baghdad. In the previous fair, only 28 UAE companies and four
Saudi firms had participated.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has completed the rehabilitation of the
Iraq-Syria pipeline which runs through Iraqi territory and the
Syrian side is busy with rehabilitating its sector.
</P>
<P>
The Arab economic daily Alam Al Yom Wednesday quoted an Iraqi
petroleum source as saying that Iraq will use this pipeline to
pump an average of 300,000 barrels of oil a day.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Syria had agreed in June last year to re-operate the
pipeline which enjoys a capacity of 1.4 million barrels per day
and links the Kirkuk oil fields in northern Iraq with the Syrian
Mediterranean port of Banias.
</P>
<P>
Syria had closed the pipeline over differences with Baghdad on
the issue of Syria's support of Tehran during the Iraq-Iran war
(1980-1988). 
</P>
</TEXT>
