<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Clears Last Landmines on Sino-Vietnamese Border (With Details) (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINGXI, GUANGXI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China announced today
that it has cleared the last landmines from its border with
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
This marks the successful completion of China's bid over the
past seven years to clear all the landmines on the Sino-Vietnamese
border.
</P>
<P>
After a spate of violent explosions in Jingxi County in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, 20 soldiers covered in
protective gears held precision mine detectors in their hands and
began searching again. They planted little red and green flags
over a 20-sq-m area when they were certain that the area was free
of landmines.
</P>
<P>
The scene was watched closely by a crowd of military
representatives, local government officials, local residents, and
journalists, standing dozens of meters away.
</P>
<P>
The 20 soldiers then fell into formation and walked out of the
area under the gaze of onlookers.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, during the war between Vietnam and China,
both countries planted several million landmines along the 2,000
km border.
</P>
<P>
China's landmine-clearing campaign was the largest in the world,
taking seven years to complete. It was carried out in two stages.
The first stage was conducted in 1993 and 1994, during which the
main thoroughfare on the border was cleared of landmines, and 19
border outlets and 30 border trading posts were opened.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts, Yunnan Province and Guangxi, bordering
Vietnam, saw their border trade volume increase by four billion
yuan. The second stage started in November 1997, and was intended
to remove all the landmines left in the border areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Clears Last Landmines on Sino-Vietnamese Border (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China spent about 200 million yuan and dispatched 2,000
soldiers to clear the mines, and there were several casualties in
the course of the work.
</P>
<P>
This undertaking has demonstrated the Chinese government's
sincere wish and firm determination to maintain good relations and
expand friendship with its neighbors, safeguard peace and advance
its open-up drive.
</P>
<P>
China cleared 2.2 million landmines over an area of more than
400-sq-km along the border in the past seven years, and destroyed
more than 400 tons of other explosives.
</P>
<P>
After making an inspection of the landmine clearing, a high-
ranking United Nations disarmament official said that Chinese
soldiers did a first-rate job, and could accomplish other
international humanitarian tasks.
</P>
<P>
Major General Qiu Daxiong, deputy commander of the Guangxi
Military Area Command, and Lu Bing, an official of the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Regional government, signed a document regarding
the transfer of land cleared of landmines at a ceremony held to
celebrate the end of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, 17,000 hectares of farmland,
pastures and forests cleared of landmines during the second stage
of landmine clearings in Guangxi are to be handed over to local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zhengfu, a 42-year-old local farmer, was all smiles. He
told reporters that for 20 years, he was afraid of risking his
life and dared not go to the border areas to farm and mine.
</P>
<P>
"I now feel safe to farm and mine for ore here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of border counties also feel relieved. Before the
landmines were cleared, they had to follow the tracks of cattle to
cross the border whenever they wanted to hold trade talks or meet
with officials of Vietnam. Local economic development in the
border areas was thus seriously hindered by the presence of the
mines.
</P>
<P>
Chinese border areas also have benefited greatly from the
landmine clearings. For instance, revenues of the seven border
counties of Guangxi went up from 200 million yuan before 1993 to
the present 500 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has reacted positively to China's
landmine-clearing campaign, and has also carried out some landmine
clearing activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
