<HEADLINE> Senior Official Calls for All-Out War Against Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAOTOU, August 11 (Xinhua)-- A senior Chinese official today
called for an all-out war against narcotics, saying that a
nationwide anti-drug campaign can not succeed without the support
of the great masses.
</P>
<P>
Luo Gan, a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and secretary of the
Committee of Political Science and Law under the CPC Central
Committee, made the remark at the National Anti-drug Conference,
which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Luo said that the final success of the anti-opium movement,
launched shortly after the founding of the People's Republic in
1949, was the result of the participation and support of the
people.
</P>
<P>
"Departments concerned should not only inherit and carry
forward past experiences, such as the mobilization of the great
masses in the war against narcotics, but should also swiftly adapt
to the new circumstances," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the narcotics problem plagues more than 70
percent of China's counties and cities, and the annual consumption
of narcotics in China is now valued at more than 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Luo urged local governments to provide more funds and equipment
for drug control to pave the way for further battles against
narcotics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
