<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Restates Ulterior Motives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- For the second time in two days,
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo reiterated that there is a
vicious motive behind the recent communal fighting across cities.
</P>
<P>
He said Tuesday in Kano, Nigeria's northern state, that he
could not fathom the explanation of the fighting as ethnic clash.
</P>
<P>
"People say it was an ethnic clash. Ethnic clash between who
and who? We have Sudanese Kano, Niger Republic Kano, Malian Kano,
Chadian Kano, etc. And what is happening? I know this is not the
handiwork of genuine Kano," he was quoted as saying by Wednesday's
Guardian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The president's pronouncement in Kano came barely 24 hours
after a similar assessment visit to Sagamu, Ogun State, where he
fingered certain opponents of the civilian administration as
having instigated the crises, to unleash mayhem on the entire
country.
</P>
<P>
Certain elements opposed to the civilian dispensation and
seeking to subvert it have instigated the recent ethnic fighting
in Sagamu and Kano, he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Later on Monday, he restated the federal government's resolve
to spare no effort in enforcing peace at the communal clash
points.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said Tuesday in Kano that Nigeria, as a secular
society, could not progress if it continues to witness bloody
communal clashes.
</P>
<P>
He deplored the recent conflict, saying it did not show the
bond of love, brotherhood, unity to foster peaceful co-existence
among diverse ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
He urged Nigerians to be their brothers' keepers. "We cannot
march forward in this country if we continue with this kind of
crisis."
</P>
<P>
In Anambra State late, Obasanjo regretted Monday that elders in
the communities no longer seemed to wield their traditional
mediatory influence in crises.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the theater of bitter warfare between
Aguleri, Umuleri and Umuoba Anam communities, the president was
disturbed by the scenes of devastation at the area, where indigene
engaged in blood-letting and wanton destruction since 1995 when an
86-year-old animosity flared again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
