<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Extend Losses on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Share prices remained
nose-dived on Singapore Stock Market Wednesday as worries over a
potential hike in U.S. interest rates and currency woes continued
to dampen the market sentiment despite the positive second quarter
economic results in the country.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) dropped 35.03 points to
end at 1,987.53 points, falling through the 2,000-point mark for
the first time in two months.
</P>
<P>
The total volume increased to 246.05 million shares valued at
427.21 Singapore dollars (about 255.81 million U.S. dollars).
Decliners outpaced advancers by 239 to 70 with 136 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
AFP continued to top the volume list of the day as 15.21
million units of the stock changed hands. Hotung was the second
heavily traded share with a turnover of 12.10 million units. Gen
Int was the next with 10.77 million counters traded.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Sem and Venture led the gainers of the day as they went
up 40 cents to close at 16.50 and 14.50 Singapore dollars
respectively. F&AMP;N edged up 20 cents to finish at 6.75 Singapore
dollars. DelGro 500 inched up 10 cents to end at 4.94 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS F was the biggest loser of the day as it
incurred a loss of 80 cents to close at 20.00 Singapore dollars.
DBS and UOB F sank 70 cents to finish at 17.20 and 10.50 Singapore
dollars respectively. OCBC F retreated 60 cents to end at 12.10
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the overnight fall on Wall Street was one of the
factors that dragged down the share prices.
</P>
<P>
The market was consolidating ahead of a possible rise in
interest rates as the U.S. Federal Reserve's rate setting
committee meets on August 24 and is widely expected to raise
rates.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said investors sold bank shares in what is seen as
rotational selling after the release of half-year earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
