<HEADLINE> Thailand to Hold Meetings with Neighbors on Curbing Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 11 (Xinhua) - Thailand will hold a meeting with
neighboring Myanmar to discuss ways to suppress drug trafficking
along the border between the two countries, Minister to Prime
Minister's Office Jurin Laksanavisit said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be held in the southern Thai province of
Ranong on August 17 and 18, said the minister after meeting with
Myanmar ambassador to Thailand Wednesday morning at the Government
House.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third joint meeting between the two countries to
discuss problems of cross-border drug trafficking over the past
one year, said Jurin, who oversees the Office of the Narcotics
Control Board (ONCB).
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also aim to beef up the joint narcotics
cooperation, which was agreed by Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
and Myanmar's top leader General Tan Shwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ONCB secretary-general Payont Pansri said that a
separate meeting between Thai narcotics officers and their Lao
counterparts would be held on August 22 in Laos' central province
of Suvannakhet to seek ways to curb the flow of drugs from Laos.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking had been more rampant along Thailand's
northeastern border adjacent to Laos, following a fierce crackdown
by Thai security officers, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
