<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-Confidence Motion Against Japanese Cabinet Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives (
lower house) on Wednesday voted down a no-confidence motion
against Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The motion was rejected with 134 votes in favor and 354 against.
The ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), its coalition partner
Liberal Party (LP) and opposition New Komeito party opposed the
motion, while three opposition parties supported the measure.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ)
submitted the motion late Tuesday night in a bid to block a set of
controversial wiretapping bills from becoming law.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Communist Party (JCP) and the Social Democratic
Party (SDP), which oppose the legislation, joined the DPJ in
backing the motion.
</P>
<P>
The wiretapping bills, which will allow law enforcement
authorities to wiretap communications during investigations into
organized crime, were railroaded through the upper house's
judicial panel Monday by the LDP, LP and New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
The DPJ, JCP and SDP protested against the forced passage of
the three-bill package, saying the committee vote was invalid.
</P>
<P>
The government says the wiretapping legislation would be a
major weapon against organized crime, such as crimes linked to the
AUM Shinrikyo cult, and gun and drug violations committed by crime
syndicates.
</P>
<P>
Critics argue the legislation could infringe on constitutional
provisions regarding the secrecy of communications and protection
of privacy.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's lower house session, DPJ Secretary General
Tsutomu Hata criticized the Obuchi cabinet and urged a dissolution
of the house.
</P>
<P>
The year-old Obuchi cabinet is "a dangerous administration"
that tries to enact controversial bills by ignoring Diet (
parliament) discussions, Hata told the lower house prior to the
voting.
</P>
<P>
The LDP, LP and New Komeito have an overwhelming majority in
the 500-member lower chamber with a combined force of 357. The
three parties also have a combined majority in the upper house.
</P>
<P>
If the no-confidence motion is passed, it would force the
cabinet to either dissolve the lower chamber or step down en masse
within 10 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
