<HEADLINE> China Eastern Airlines to Fly First From Pudong Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China Eastern Airlines, the
largest carrier based in Shanghai, will make the first flight from
the city's new Pudong Airport, a high-ranking company official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Changwu, managing director of Eastern Airlines, disclosed
the company's three-phase flight plans at the airport, which is
scheduled to begin at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will be from October 1 to October 30, with over
20 flights a week, said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
During the second phase, from October 31 to March 25, 2000, the
airlines will increase the number of flights to over 100 a week.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on March 26, 2000, China Eastern Airlines expects to
establish a domestic air-route network covering east China,
according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
China Eastern Airlines will also transfer most of its cargo
flights to the new airport in Pudong, Zhou added.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong Airport, which is Shanghai's second international
airport after Hongqiao, currently has a main building covering an
area of 280,000 square meters, and a 4,000-meter-long primary
runway.
</P>
<P>
It is designed to accommodate up to 126,000 landings and take-
offs a year, and to handle 20 million passengers and 750,000 tons
of freight annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
