<HEADLINE> More Help Urged for Disabled in Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Governments in southern African
countries should offer more help to the disabled, the federation
of the disabled in southern Africa and non-government
organizations have called.
</P>
<P>
The call was made Tuesday at the opening ceremony of a
conference of the disabled, Noticias newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference expressed their wishes that
governments should map out strategies and take concrete actions to
help the disabled, not mere leave on lip service.
</P>
<P>
The federation said in a statement that government in the
region, where hundreds of thousands are suffering from land mines,
should give green lights to the international land mine ban
convention.
</P>
<P>
Farida Gulamo, chairman of the Mozambican Association of the
Disabled, said that it is time for the Mozambican government to
take action to offer more help to the disabled and destroy the
existing land mines, since the government has approved the land
mine ban convention.
</P>
<P>
Gulamo said that the participation of the whole society is very
 important in safeguarding the rights of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Various sectors of the society and the region should take
coordinated actions in solving the problems facing the disabled,
for the social and economic
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts from nine countries in southern Africa
are attending the conference which is to end on August 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
