<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urges India to Abolish Special Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan Wednesday urged India to
abolish the Special Additional Duty (SAD) on imports and freely
allow remittances abroad to help investment flow from Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Vice Minister of Ministry of International Trade and
Industry Hisamitsu Arai also wanted India to scrap its
"unfriendly" auto policy and liberalize operations of foreign
trading companies.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters here after his meeting with Indian Finance
Minister Yashwant Sinha that Sinha has promised to look into the
concerns raised by Japan.
</P>
<P>
Arai, who is here to attend the first ever India-Japan
Investment Dialogue, said high import tariffs and the SAD were
impeding fresh Japanese investments in India.
</P>
<P>
India and Japan Tuesday agreed to set up a working group and
three sector-specific sub-groups to facilitate investments between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The three sub-groups for information technology, infrastructure
and food processing will monitor, coordinate and follow up
decisions taken by the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
