<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Furniture Exhibition Proceeds in Nigeria Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Furniture makers Tuesday turned
the ground floor of the Nigerian National Assembly in Abuja into
an exhibition gallery following last week's approval of furniture
allowance for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
By 8:45 a.m. Monday, one of the many furniture firms had taken
a large chunk of space to showcase the qualitative nature of
furniture, which members of the Senate and House of
Representatives are expected to procure, the Guardian newspaper
reported Wednesday
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the furniture exhibition has the
approval of Alhaji Salim, the clerk of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Monday's proceedings, some members visited the
exhibition stands before going in for committee deliberations,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition coincided with a hot protest by the Umbrella
Labor Union for Nigerian workers Tuesday in front of the assembly
building, with protesters calling the furniture allowance a
"outrageous" move.
</P>
<P>
The government, after hot debate, agreed last week to pay each
member of the 109-member Senate 3.5 million naira (about 37,000 US
dollars) and their counterparts in the 360-member House 2.5
million naira (26,000 US dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
The protesters Tuesday branded the awards "repulsive,
provocative and princely lifestyles in the midst of pervasive and
abject poverty." The Union president said it could not be
justified with the country's economic realities.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria is today a poverty afflicted nation, per capita income
is about 260 U.S. dollars per annum and the minimum wage is 3,000
naira (31 US dollars) ," he said.
</P>
<P>
The furniture allowance issue has become quite a focus in the
country recently with some newspapers dubbing it the "furniture
gate".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multinationals to Attend China Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 multinational
corporations will participate in the upcoming '99 China Fair for
International Investment and Trade, slated for September 8-12 in
the eastern port city of Xiamen, Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Department of Foreign Investment
Administration under the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) told Xinhua on Wednesday that multinationals
attending the fair include such big names as Motorola, Ericsson,
Nokia, Siemens, Canon, Mobil, and Sony.
</P>
<P>
Corporations planning to set up exhibitions at the fair are
involved in motor vehicles and parts, mobile telecommunications,
construction materials, power equipment, and family appliances.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, said that all of China'
s 31 provincial localities will send delegations to the fair, and
there also will be delegations from some ministries and national
economic organizations.
</P>
<P>
Cao Degan, deputy governor of Fujian and vice-chairman of the
fair's organizing committee, said at a recent meeting that more
attention will be paid to promoting the fair worldwide via many
means, including the Internet.
</P>
<P>
This annual fair is China's only trade and investment event on
a nationwide scale. More than 6,000 businesspeople from home and
abroad participated in the fair last year.
</P>
<P>
China registered a decline in overseas investment in terms of
both contractual volume and paid-in volume in the first half this
year, according to figures released by MOFTEC.
</P>
<P>
China approved a total of 8,052 new overseas-invested projects
between January and June, which represented a drop of 16.71
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The newly approved projects involve 19.39 billion U.S. dollars
of contractual overseas investment, a decline of 19.87 percent on
a year-on-year basis. The volume of overseas investment already in
place was 18.57 billion U.S. dollars for the half, down by 9.21
percent from a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
