<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Suggested to Develop Government Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Economic
Association President R. Thillainathan Wednesday suggested that
the government bond market be developed further so that it can
serve as a benchmark yield curve.
</P>
<P>
Thillainathan made the suggestion as he said that the active
and liquid cross currency swap market that provided a proxy yield
curve and was used by investors to decide on bond issues and
trading in bonds has been absent following the currency controls,
making it difficult for traders to buy and sell.
</P>
<P>
The government should issue Malaysian Government Securities
(MGS) papers from time to time even if it does not intend to
borrow, Thillainathan said at the two-day Malaysian Capital Market
seminar which opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thillainathan suggested better cooperation between the various
authorities that regulated the local bond market.
</P>
<P>
The existing regulatory institutions should collaborate so that
there will not be a conflict of interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
There is more than one regulator for the market at present in
Malaysia. The most important one is the central bank while others
include the Securities Commission and the Registrar of Companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
