<HEADLINE> Australians Support Proposed Charter Preamble: Democrats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deal ended the row over the recognition of Aborigines and
Torres Strait Islanders by referring to their "deep kinship" with
the land.
</P>
<P>
The new proposed preamble said the Australians honor "Aborigines
and Torres Strait Islanders, the nation's first people, for their
deep kinship with their lands and for their ancient and continuing
cultures which enrich the life of our country."
</P>
<P>
It ditched the controversial reference of mateship to
Aborigines and Torre Strait Islanders.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the wording that we have achieved is better
than any suggested before and indeed will advance the cause of
reconciliation," Lees told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party and the Democrats had demanded the preamble refer
to Aboriginal custodianship, a word Prime Minister John Howard
refused to accept. 
</P>
