<HEADLINE> Singapore Elected President's Power Is Limited, Non-Executive: Lee Kuan Yew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew has said that his country's elected president only has
limited, non-executive power and there can only one center of
government in the country, "The Straits Times" reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with the paper, the senior minister
detailed on limits of the elected president's power to debunk
popular misconceptions on the role of an elected president and to
stress the importance of rotating the presidency among the races.
</P>
<P>
Lee, the main architect of the elected presidency, said the
elected president was never intended to be an executive office to
contest the government's power.
</P>
<P>
Until there is a rogue government that will drain past reserves
or undermine the higher echelons of the public service, the
president's role remains largely ceremonial, he said, adding there
is a lot of misconception of what is required of an elected
president in the country.
</P>
<P>
His comments came in response to the current debate about the
role of the elected president and qualities needed to do the job.
</P>
<P>
Lee was quoted as stressing in the interview that "you do not
have two sources of executive power. The executive power is in the
prime minister and his cabinet and they are answerable to
parliament."
</P>
<P>
"The president is elected by the people to do a specific job to
block bad actions by a bad government but not to interfere in the
running of the government."
</P>
<P>
"He has no executive powers to initiate anything nor to stop
the government from doing something other than spending reserves
and making bad appointments."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fact that the elected president system was
crafted carefully and passed into law in 1992 after he first
broached the office publicly in 1984, Lee emphasized that the
president was not intended as a counter-focus of power, saying "He
can not be, because then the government will be immobilized. We do
not have a presidential system like the United states."
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the current public discussion that the president
must be independent so that the president can be an effective
check on the government, Lee said there is ignorance about the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
While elaborating the Constitution, the senior minister said
that the president can not make speeches against the government,
can not act independently of the government other than to block it
and can not act against wishes of the government except when the
government wants to do things the president is entitled to veto.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question why he refuses to take the job as a
president, Lee was quoted as saying that "You need a very wise,
bright, patient sort of person. I would be the first to say that I
am not qualified for the job because I'm an activist. So when
people thought that I was crafting this job for myself, they were
completely wrong."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
