<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- French Defense Minister Alain Richard said Tuesday
that the French peacekeepers had taken appropriate measures to
curb the violence of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo's northern city of
Kosovska Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to create safe conditions for all Kosovars,
said the minister, who was on a one-day trip to Kosovo, when
commenting three days of clashes between French troops and Kosovo
Albanians in Kosovska Mitrovica. (Yugoslavia-France-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan Interior Minister Ignacio Arcaya on
Tuesday denied any compromise with the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia (FARC) on the release of eight hostages aboard a plane
hijacked on June 30.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that the issuing of a FARC statement about the
release of hostages has been part of the negotiations between the
Venezuelan government and the Colombian leftist rebels. Arcaya
insisted that he did not hold talks with any member of the FARC.
(Venezuela-Hostage Release)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia on Tuesday accused the U.N. mission and
the international peacekeepers in Kosovo of failing to fully
implement the related U.N. resolution on Kosovo, which it said has
caused "a fairly complicated and serious situation" in the
province.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo has become "very complicated and
serious" as the U.N. special mission and the peacekeeping force
did not earnestly implement the resolution adopted earlier by the
U.N. Security Council, said Zoran Andelkovic, chairman of Kosovo's
Provisional Executive Committee, in Pristina, capital of Kosovo.
(Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Situation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PEMH -- The Cambodian National Assembly Wednesday
approved a new law that allows an extension of the detention
without trial of captured Khmer Rouge leaders for up to three
years.
</P>
<P>
The new law would allow a court to detain Khmer Rouge leader Ta
Mok for up to three years without a trial, instead of the six
months now mandated by a penal law. (Cambodia-Law-Khmer Rouge)
</P>
</TEXT>
