<HEADLINE> Mauritian, Indian Companies to Invest in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Five Mauritian and Indian
companies have pledged to invest in Botswana, creating thousands
of jobs before the end of the year, South Africa's Business Day
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The investment fitted in with the government's plan to
diversify the diamond-dependent economy, the paper quoted
Botswana Export Development and Investment Authority's promotions
manager, Rose Tatedi, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This will help us to reduce the high rate of unemployment and
assist with the transfer of much-needed skills into the country,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The country of 1.5 million people has an unemployment rate of
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The five companies which have pledged investment in the country
are in textiles and garments, and nail and metal components.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the companies will be looking at the regional market
to export their products. However, most of the textile and
garments industries will be mainly exporting to the United States
and Britain, said Tatedi.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Botswana abolished all foreign exchange
controls as an additional incentive for foreign direct investment.
The country also boasts political stability and free market
policies conducive to private sector development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
