<HEADLINE> Sparrows Gaining Protection in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Sparrows, one of China's
traditional four evils along with the mosquito, the fly, and the
mouse, is now gaining some protection in East China's Shandong
Province after decades of over-killing.
</P>
<P>
Sparrows have been traditionally seen as harmful because they
flutter on the crop fields and steal grain away from people.
However, experts have discovered that sparrows eat more worms than
grain, and are generally good for the mankind.
</P>
<P>
In addition, hundreds of thousands of sparrows were lost in
Shandong to the novelty-seeking appetites of people in southern
China.
</P>
<P>
Han Yunchi, an official of an animal protection organization,
said that sparrows also help spread pollen, which contributes
tremendously to agricultural production, and that their role in
the ecological balance cannot be replaced.
</P>
<P>
However, he recalled that rampant killings have severely
affected the ecological balance, resulting in an overwhelming
growth of worms and insects in the cropfields, and that the
Shandong Provincial Government is planning a survey to determine
the size of sparrow population in order to map out protective
measures.
</P>
<P>
As of now, the hunting, trading, or killing of sparrows will
receive "due punishment," said Han. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
