<HEADLINE> Feature: "Seeking Roots" Under the Five-Star Red Flag (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hwang is staring at the flag, deep in thought, and although he
is just a freshman, he dreams of working for China after
graduating from the university.
</P>
<P>
Robert Woo left China 13 years ago, and now has returned with
his 9-year-old daughter. When he sees the raising of the national
flag once again, his face beams with excitement
</P>
<P>
When the flag reaches the top of the pole, Kathy Chiang says
with tears in her eyes that she is deeply touched each time she
hears the national anthem, because her mother loves it.
</P>
<P>
She said that great changes have taken place in China, and it
is necessary to have the youth learn about the real China.
</P>
<P>
Helena Yan, the leader of the group, noted that the national
flag is the symbol of the country, and that these American kids
must first come to know something about China before they can find
their roots. Attending the flag-hoisting ceremony in Tian'anmen
Square has special significance, and is a good place to begin, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Fifty days from now, on the same square, the largest in the
world, a splendid celebration marking the 50th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China will be underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
