<HEADLINE> Feature: "Seeking Roots" Under the Five-Star Red Flag (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Lawscanse Hwang, a 20-year-old
Chinese-American, is standing on the Jinshui Bridge in front of
the Tian'anmen Rostrum, and looks very excited.
</P>
<P>
Several minutes later he will, for the first time, attend the
flag-hoisting ceremony on the newly renovated Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
"I am very exited to find my roots under the national flag,"
said Hwang, one of the members of the '99 Chinese-American Youth "
Roots-Seeking Tour."
</P>
<P>
None of the kids on this tour group have ever attended the
national flag-hoisting ceremony before, and some of them have
never before seen the Five-Star Red Flag of China.
</P>
<P>
Facing the rising sun, 36 guards protecting the national flag
come out from the Tian'anmen Rostrum, pass over the Jinshui Bridge
and Chang'an Avenue, and walk toward Tian'anmen Square accompanied
by the strains of "Sing for the Motherland."
</P>
<P>
At 5:20, as the national flag is hoisted and the national
anthem plays, the rising sun casts its light on the flag, and on
the faces of the American kids.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. custom, people put their right hand over
their heart when the national flag is hoisted, but these American
youngsters of Chinese descent are now saluting the flag the
Chinese way, by looking directly at the Five-Star Banner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
