<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Indicate Need of More Aid to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- British officials have indicated
the need to provide more aid to development projects in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The officials of Britain's International Development Office
made the call after meetings on Tuesday with Egyptian officials in
charge of environment protection, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the British delegation, which arrived in Cairo
on Monday, said the kingdom's aid to Egypt stands at an annual 7
million pounds sterling (11.83 million U.S. dollars), the
English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Of the aid, five million pounds (8.45 million dollars) are
allocated for projects aimed at environmental protection in Egypt,
the newspaper quoted the sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in protecting environment in Egypt topped the
agenda of a recent visit to Britain by Egyptian Minister of State
for Environmental Affairs Nadia Makram Ebeid, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 2 million pounds (3.38 million dollars) are for
literacy and adult education programs and cooperation with Egypt's
Social Fund for Development in improving women's standard of
living in southern governorates' rural areas by setting up small
businesses for them, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The program of aid to Egypt in the coming period will concentrate
on offering technical assistance to upgrade sewerage facilities
in Cairo, they added.
</P>
<P>
The British delegation of the International Development Office,
which is in charge of Britain's economic aid to developing
countries, will inspect a number of development projects the
country has helped create in southern Egypt, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
