<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Germany Agree on All-cargo Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The governments of the
Philippines and Germany have agreed to have an all-cargo flights
between the two countries in view of the rising demand for the
service, Philippine News Agency (PNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The existing Philippine-German air agreement does not allow
all-cargo flights between the two countries, the PNA said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine Civil Aeronautics Board (CAB) held talks
with representatives of the civil aviation body and airline
companies of Germany to amend the air services agreement signed in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Under the new agreement, the German Airlines will have three
all-cargo flights per week starting in April 2000, while the
Philippines will also have the same frequencies, the PNA quoted
CAB Executive Director Guia Martinez as saying.
</P>
<P>
The German civil aviation would either assign Lufthansa or
Luftransport-Unternchmen to utilize these frequencies.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Lufthansa operates seven round-trip passenger/cargo
flights per week from Germany to the Philippines and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines (PAL) usually flies to Germany but stopped
operations shortly after the onset of its financial woes in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Shuts Down Pepsi Production Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian Ministry of Health
on Tuesday decided to close one production line at a local
bottling plant of Pepsi Cola for one week after laboratory tests
proved that soft drinks produced by the plant were contaminated.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Issaq Maraqah said his ministry has discussed
the decision with the cabinet to suspend the plant's production of
Miranda, Pepsi and 7UP for one week before taking the plant to
court, Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, other production lines for canisters and plastic
bottles were not closed since the decision only covered glass
bottles, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Impurities were detected during laboratory tests on the glass
bottles and the factory seemed to lack hygienic standards for the
reusable bottles as well as the cleaning capacity for the bottles.
</P>
<P>
Cement pieces and grease were found in some bottles while
others contained plastic and wooden substances, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the suspension of the production line could be
indefinite other than one week.
</P>
<P>
"The production line will be closed until the plant proves
it ensures clean products that the ministry required," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pepsi products are the biggest source of soft drinks in
stores and supermarkets of the desert kingdom, but many of
the products are locally packed and bottled under licenses from
the U.S. Pepsi company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
