<HEADLINE> Indonesian FM Meets U.N. Secretary General's Special Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General's special
envoy to East Timor issue Jamsheed Marker said that the situation
in the territory after the August 30 autonomy ballot is very very
important.
</P>
<P>
The situation will be discussed in a tripartite senior official
meeting between representatives of Indonesia, Portugal and U.N.
secretary general here on August 12-13.
</P>
<P>
"We had a preliminary discussion on the issue. I took his
advice and guidance at the meeting which we are going to have at
the senior official level, starting tomorrow," Marker told
reporters after an hour meeting with Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Alatas raised some important issues which will be
discussed in the meeting, but he was not in a position to announce
the issues now.
</P>
<P>
"I am not in the position to tell you right now but I am
satisfied and encouraged about my meeting with Mr. Alatas, and I
look forward to the very productive discussion at the senior
official meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the last day of the two-day meeting, he said, all delegates
will issue a joint communique informing about what has been talked
about and what decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
Asked his comment on an international opinion that the
situation in East Timor will be delicate, Marker said what is
clear to the U.N. is that the situation will be very very
important and appropriate measures need to be taken.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will allow the territory's people to choose whether
their homeland should become an autonomous region within Indonesia
or totally independent. If a majority of them reject the offer,
the territory will peacefully separate from the Unitary State of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Until the end of the registration process on August 8, 446,666
East Timorese had registered inside and outside the territory.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
