<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Peace Process Hopeful: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The peace process in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), though still quite
fragile, is hopeful, The New Vision newspaper, Uganda's leading
daily newspaper sponsored by the government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, the newspaper said that although the DRC
continues to be confounding, it is not as intractable as many have
feared.
</P>
<P>
Even the weekend clashes between the Rally for Congolese
Democracy (RCD) led by Emile IIunga and the Ugandan troops, the
last twist of event in the peace process, could not spoil the
whole process.
</P>
<P>
"When the situation is viewed in its entirety, there is reason
to be hopeful. A few short months ago, it was inconceivable that
Laurent Kabila (DRC President) could sit down for discussions with
his erstwhile foes," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
A lot of the saber-rattling from the various sides promised
little progress, but a ray of light appeared at the end of the
tunnel in Libya when Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and his DRC
counterpart Laurent Kabila signed what was called a declaration of
intent.
</P>
<P>
This coalesced into greater promise with last month's Lusaka
accord signed by a host of regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, leaders from Uganda, Rwanda met in South
Africa to try to remove the last tumbling block to the
implementation of the accord. The Pretoria talks mandated a team
to travel to the DRC to continue exploring ways to achieve a
cessation of hostilities, the editorial added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
