<HEADLINE> Rwandans Threaten to Fight Back If Attacked by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA)
has warned that they would return fire if their positions in
Kisangani, the third largest city in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC), was attacked by Ugandan troops.
</P>
<P>
The threat, made by Rwandan government spokesman Wilson
Rutayisire Tuesday, comes after the Uganda People's Defense Forces
engaged the Goma faction of the Rally for Congolese Democracy
(RCD), the Monitor daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rutayisire dismissed the claims that the RPA had been chased
from its Kisangani Airport base, saying that the last weekend's
fighting was entirely a matter between the RCD-Goma and the
Ugandan forces although some RPA soldiers were injured in the
exchange for fire.
</P>
<P>
The RPA will defend themselves decisively if they are attacked
by the Ugandan troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also accused Uganda's Army Chief of Staff James
Kazini, who heads the Ugandan troops operation in the DRC, of
corrupting the verification process initiated by regional leaders
in Zambia on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda support different factions after the RCD
split into two groups in May this year. Kigali backs the faction
based in Goma while Kampala is behind the group with headquarters
in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Now both countries have been urged to persuade rebels to
endorse the Lusaka ceasefire agreement in order to put the peace
process in the DRC back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
