<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Parliament Approves New Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PEMH, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian National Assembly
Wednesday approved a new law in an emergency session that allows
an extension of the detention without trial of captured Khmer
Rouge leaders up to three years.
</P>
<P>
The law, passed with 94 votes for out of 106 parliamentarians
attending the session, would allow a court to detain Khmer Rouge
leader Ta Mok for up to three years without trial, instead of the
six months now mandated by law.
</P>
<P>
The new law states that "for the case of crime of genocide, war
crime and crime against humanity which already mentioned in the
United Nations Convention, the pre-detention can be extended once
a year, but the duration of such extension must not be over three
years."
</P>
<P>
Assembly President Prince Ranariddh said after the session that
according to this law, Ta Mok will be charged with the law of
outlawing the Khmer Rouge and the law on genocide crimes when the
law is adopted.
</P>
<P>
Ta Mok was arrested on March 6 and has been detained in Phnom
Penh since then. Under Article 14 of Cambodia's current penal
code, Ta Mok must be tried within a month.
</P>
<P>
The court has earlier considered having double trials if a new
law is not passed. The first trial will be by a 1994 law banning
the Khmer Rouge, and the second one by a law on genocide.
</P>
<P>
Key lawmakers of Assembly's legislation committee reached a
compromise agreement on the legislation last week, which would
delay the trial of military chief Ta Mok and prevent
potentially-troubling revelations from surfacing.
</P>
<P>
Some argue the law will buy the government time to forge an
agreement with the United Nations for a tribunal to prosecute
Khmer Rouge leaders for crimes committed from 1975 to 1979. The
law would also allow the government to try Ta Mok on crimes of
genocide and crimes against humanity, instead of solely on a 1994
law banning the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
But the new law was attacked by human rights groups and
opposition party members who said it is a delaying tactic designed
to put the trial off indefinitely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
