<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Stimulus Package Applauded, But No Cure-All Panacea(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The latest economic stimulus
package announced Tuesday by the Thai cabinet was warmly received
by local business people. However, analysts warned it was not a
cure-all panacea and that it will take some time before the
results would be seen.
</P>
<P>
The multi-billion-baht stimulus package aims to further spur
the economic recovery by the reduction of import duties and the
mobilization of funds.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet outlined four key aspects of the package, namely
tax and tariff measures, equity investment measures, measures to
promote the recovery of the real estate sector, and measures to
improve financing of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
The cabinet approved cuts in import duties, mainly those on raw
materials, intermediate goods and products that are not being
produced domestically, to help reduce the production cost of Thai
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
The government is also to set up three new funds -- the Equity
Fund, the Thailand Recovery Fund, and the Fund for Venture Capital
Investment in SMEs -- to encourage the debt-restructuring of the
corporate sector and boost the investment of the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Equity Fund will be established to seek investment in
large-scale enterprises in Thailand which are competitive but so
far have been denied liquidity from the banking system.
</P>
<P>
The Thailand Recovery Fund, in which the Asian Development Bank
will become a key partner, will serve medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To support small-scale enterprises, the state-controlled Small
Industry Finance Cooperation will be providing soft-loan funding
to the sector.
</P>
<P>
The government will also mobilize another 67 billion baht (1.8
billion dollars) to create the liquidity and improve the
consumers' demand in the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal, the Government Housing Bank will issue a
housing bond worth 46 billion baht (1.24 billion dollars) with
three to five-year maturity, while the state-run Secondary
Mortgage Corporation will raise another four billion baht (108
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to inject additional 17 billion baht
(459.5 million dollars) in National Housing Authority as part of
the state agency's reserve to purchase and develop the incomplete
housing project for sale to the small income people.
</P>
<P>
The government also enacted a series of ongoing measures to
support SMEs, including arranging over 35 billion baht (945.9
million dollars) in credit for SMEs through the specialized
financial institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Stimulus Package Applauded, But No Cure-All Panacea(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said that while the
measures would affect state revenues, it would improve corporate
earnings and employment and lead to long-term gains in the
country's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The new stimulus package is the third one produced by the Chuan
Leekpai government over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
On August 14 1998, the government introduced a 300-billion-baht
(8.1-billion-dollar) program to recapitalize the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, 1999, the government announced tax cuts worth 130
billion baht (3.5 billion dollars) and new spending to help
stimulate consumer demand and create up to 486,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
One of the distinguished characteristics of this new package is
that it contains measures to boost the real sector and the real
estate market.
</P>
<P>
This aims to silence those critics who say that the government
has been paying too much attention to tackling the financial
sector at the expense of the real sector.
</P>
<P>
Thamma Pinsukarnchana, director of the Federation of Thai
Industries, said the tariff cuts would raise profits for exporters
by cutting production costs.
</P>
<P>
Soonthorn Nikomrut, president of the Rubber Holders'
Cooperatives Federation of Thailand, said the package would help
local businesses, particularly farmers and agribusinesses reliant
on imports such as fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
However, it is widely agreed that the package came too late as
many firms have been on the verge of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the results of the package would not be seen in a
short period of time.
</P>
<P>
According to Nimit Nontapuntawat, executive vice-president of
Bangkok Bank, the short-term impact of the package would be mainly
in sentiment and increased confidence, with the actual result not
to be felt until mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said despite the new package, underlying problems
remain in financial and corporate sectors.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans are still persistently high, accounting
for 47.7 percent of the total loans in the banking system at the
end of May.
</P>
<P>
This reflects economic weakness, the slow pace of corporate
debt restructuring and the unwillingness of the banking sector to
deal with its won problems, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They said that great challenges are still ahead for Thailand's
economic recovery, such as how the credit system can be restored,
how effectively the financial sector is reformed and how quick
corporate debt restructuring is implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
