<HEADLINE> Wreckage of Downed Pak Plane on Display in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Salvaged parts of the wreckage
of the Pakistani "Breguet Atlantique" military aircraft downed
over Gujarat were put up for display at the Prime Minister's
office Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the Pakistani naval aircraft, shot down by an
Indian Air Force (IAF) plane Tuesday, was brought here early
Wednesday morning along with some personal documents of Pakistani
navy pilots, IAF sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The documents included flight manual of the pilots and
checklist of the aircraft besides personal documents.
</P>
<P>
The salvaged wreckage brought to the capital included fuselage
wing, cable hydraulic system, one parachute, a dingy and cockpit
of the anti-submarine reconnaissance aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The salvage operations were carried out through Tuesday
afternoon in the slushy and marshy areas of Kori Creek on the
Indian side of the Indo-Pakistani border in the Kutch region of
the Southern state of Gujarat, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
IAF pressed MI-17 helicopters to airlift the parts of the
maritime surveillance aircraft, which crashed after being hit by
an air-to-air missile fired by a Mig-21 fighter on the edge of the
Arabian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an IAF spokesman rejected the Pakistani claim that
the Indian jets "violated Pakistani air space" and that "the
wreckage was well within Pakistani territory."
</P>
<P>
"How could we salvage the wreckage if it was lying on the
Pakistani side," the spokesman asked.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not rule out that some parts of the plane may
have landed on the Pakistani side as it came down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
