has issued a 10-day ultimatum to those holding illegal firearms
to surrender them to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a meet-the-people tour in the capital Nairobi
Tuesday, the president said there was proliferation of illegal
weapons in the country and the firearm holders have up by August
20 to surrender them to nearest police stations or administrative
offices, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Those who will surrender their arms within the period would not
be arrested, Moi said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that after the expire of this amnesty, the security
agents would arrest and prosecute those who defied the ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
The president urged the Kenyans to provide information to the
authorities on the whereabouts of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
Local media earlier reported that there are more than 5,000
illegal guns in the Kenyan capital and thousands at large
elsewhere in the country being used by criminals. The illegal
firearms are mainly smuggled into Kenya from the neighboring
war-stricken countries. 
