<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Reduce VAT Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has been urged
to consider the reduction of the current Value Added Tax (VAT)
rate of 17.5 percent as Zambia had the highest level in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Association of Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZACC)
chairman George Chabwera said the current VAT level impacted
negatively on businesses in the country.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Wednesday's Zambian newspaper, The Post, as
saying the reduction of the VAT levels was part of the ZACC
submissions for the proposed additions and changes to the budget
for the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Chabwera said both the high VAT levels and duty had negatively
affected companies to the point that the Zambia Revenue Authority
company tax collections had fallen due to continued losses.
</P>
<P>
A revision of the current tax regime would favor sound and
profitable operations of firms and increase collections as
companies would now start registering profits, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among other submissions is the reduction of the current 125
percent excise duty which had disadvantaged producers of beer,
carbonated drinks and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Chabwera also called on the government to further reduce duty
on raw materials to help make the locally manufactured goods more
competitive and stimulate growth of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Chabwera was commenting Tuesday on the invitation by the
Ministry of Finance and Economic Development permanent secretary
Boniface Nonde for budget submissions from the private sector and
members of the public to be included in next year's budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
