<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closed-End Loans Expected To Boost Ailing State Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Better management of closed-end
loans is expected to give money-losing state-owned enterprises an
opportunity to gradually pull out of their difficulties by means
of more profitable products, according to Chinese financial
analysts.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the nation's central bank, has
asked all commercial banks to make a greater effort to support
profitable products of these companies.
</P>
<P>
Closed-end loans first appeared in the second half of 1997
after a series of People's Bank policies that encouraged
commercial banks to provide support for the market-favored
products of money-losing companies.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the bank made a decision about managing
closed-end loans, providing regulations and verifying procedures
to standardize practices. A bank spokesman says that closed-end
loans can help companies increase profits and help commercial
banks improve their assets and management.
</P>
<P>
China's major commercial banks say that closed-end loans in the
past two years have already had good results and some state-owned
companies have recovered somewhat.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the Bank of China had provided 3.95 billion
yuan (about 477 million U.S. dollars) and 9.4 million U.S. dollars
worth of such loans to 405 money-losing companies.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China has provided the
loans for more than 500 state-owned industrial enterprises, worth
3.6 billion yuan, and 25 of the enterprises have cut their losses,
and 275 enterprises have increased profits to some degree.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts say that the central government's decision
to recognize closed-end loans as a major way to promote economic
development means a great opportunity for money-losing companies,
which are expected to do more market research and product
development to help find a way out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Posts 48.6b U.S. Dollars of External Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' external debt
has climbed up by 783 million U.S. dollars to 48.6 billion dollars
in the first quarter from 47.8 billion dollars in the end of 1998
due to the government's massive foreign borrowings, the Philippine
Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the higher debt stock, the country can still service
its debts without posing threats to the stability of the external
sector, Philippine Central Bank Governor Rafael Buenaventura was
quoted as saying in a speech before the House of Representatives
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In January-April, the nation's debt-service ratio stood at a
comfortable level of 12.3 percent, which means for every dollar
the exporters earn, 0.12 dollar will be set aside for debt
payments, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Of the entire foreign debt, according to Burenaventura, medium-
to long-term loans account for 86 percent or 41.796 billion
dollars, which is the bulk, while those which are short-term
comprised only 14 percent or 6.804 billion dollars of the total.
</P>
<P>
During the financial crisis of the 1980s, short-term commercial
bank loans formed the majority of the debt stock, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the peso appreciated by 27.5 centavos to close at
38.89 pesos to the dollar Tuesday from the previous day's 39.165
pesos to the dollar due to an alleged intervention by the central
bank.
</P>
<P>
The traders added the central bank sold dollars through
unidentified "conduit banks."
</P>
<P>
This sale, however, was again denied by central bank officials
who said the government is leaving the pesos to market forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
