<HEADLINE> Wreckage of Downed Pakistani Plane Brought to Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The wreckage of the Pakistani
naval aircraft, shot down by an Indian Air Force (IAF) plane
Tuesday, was brought to New Delhi early Wednesday morning along
with some personal documents of Pakistani navy pilots.
</P>
<P>
The documents recovered included a flight manual of the pilots
and the checklist of the aircraft besides some personal documents,
IAF sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The salvaged wreckage brought to New Delhi included a fuselage
wing, a cable hydraulic system, one parachute, a dingy and the
cockpit of the anti-submarine reconnaissance aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Some bank accounts of Pakistani pilots, credit card vouchers
and shoes were also found, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The salvage operations were carried out throughout Tuesday
afternoon in the slushy and marshy areas of Kori Creek on the
Indian side of the Indo-Pakistani border in the Kutch region of
the Southern state of Gujarat, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
IAF pressed MI-17 helicopters into service to airlift the parts
of the maritime surveillance aircraft, which crashed after being
hit by an air-to-air missile fired by a Mig-21 fighter on the edge
of the Arabian Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
