<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Consumer Confidence in Economy Boosted: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai consumers' confidence in a
resurgent economy and possible recovery over the next six months
had been boosted in July, according to a survey available on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
All economic indicators in July showed improvement,
particularly the index measuring the confidence of consumers in
the future of the Thai economy, noted a survey conducted by the
economic and business center of the University of the Thai Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence index rose to 106.2 points in July,
topping 100 for the first time after hovering between 60 and 80
points in the past seven months. The index only recorded 85.8
points in June.
</P>
<P>
The center based its findings on interviews with 1,823 people
of all ages nationwide. The respondents were asked about their
confidence in the Thai economy overall, employment prospects, and
expected income in the future.
</P>
<P>
The index has a full scale of 200 points, providing a snapshot
view of the economy. Under the index scale, between 100-200 points
reflect consumers' full confidence in economic growth, with
exactly 100 showing the economy remains in good shape. An index
below 100 shows people believe the economy is in poor shape.
</P>
<P>
The index for employment prospects in July edged up to 61.2
points from 48.6 points in June and the index for expected income
in the future at 103.9 points compared with 101.4 points in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Environment-Friendly Housing Units Up For Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A housing complex in Beijing's
Fangshan District is China's first to use new environment-friendly
technology, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The Beiluchun Housing Complex was built on 14.46 hectares of
land to provide 32.22 percent of the units with lawns. Residents
separate the garbage by type for burning or recycling and the heat
generated by the process can be used as energy-saving heat for the
complex.
</P>
<P>
There is also a sewage treatment plant whose treated water is
used on the lawns and for cleaning the community's streets. Units
have their own heating system to save energy and stop air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hui, who helped design the complex, told Xinhua that
using these high-tech methods does not add a significant amount to
building costs and the recycling has obvious benefits in reduced
energy costs.
</P>
<P>
The complex is expected to provide a good example for China's
housing development, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
