<HEADLINE> Poorly Run Chinese Job Training Centers Penalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) recently revoked the licenses of
two centers that train Chinese laborers for work overseas as part
of its efforts to improve the level of laborers, International
Economic Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The two centers were reportedly accused of improper or
inadequate training and had even sold graduation certificates to
untrained persons. One other center was also criticized and
ordered to improve its work because of mismanagement and the small
number of people who completed courses in 1998, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC has approved more than 160 centers to train people to
work abroad since 1995 and over 500,000 people have passed through
the training programs. 
