<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankers Welcome Decision To Expand Foreign Involvement In RMB Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China's recent decision to
further loosen restrictions on foreign banks doing business in
yuan has been welcomed by both domestic and overseas bankers
because it provides opportunities for foreign banks to increase
activities in China and for Chinese bankers to improve their
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks in Shanghai now can look for customers in Jiangsu
and Zhejiang provinces and banks in Shenzhen can do yuan-based
business in Hunan and Guangdong provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, since some restrictions on the scale of
business have been eased. Previously, foreign banks could only
deal in yuan on a trial basis in Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
T. C. Kwan, the president of the Bank of East Asia's Shanghai
Branch, says that the move may help increase yuan funding sources
for foreign banks, something that has been a problem for them.
Kwan's branch started doing business in yuan last year and now
handles deposits and loans in yuan.
</P>
<P>
Nie Ming, the vice president of Fuji Bank's Shanghai branch,
says that his bank has paid close attention to the new policy
although it doesn't deal in yuan right now, but is considering
applying for a license because there's a great deal of demand from
customers.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Lu, the president of the Bank of China's Shanghai branch,
admits that Chinese banks have felt the pressure of growing
competition from foreign banks, but says that it could help lead
to further reforms.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jiasheng, the president of the Bank of Communications'
Shanghai branch, says that his bank is preparing a cooperation
program with foreign banks in Shanghai, Jiangsu, and Zhejiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
