<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parliament Approves New Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PEMH, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian National
Assembly Wednesday approved a new law that allows an extension of
the detention without trial of captured Khmer Rouge leaders for up
to three years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 106 out of 122 parliamentarians attended an
emergency session and the law was passed with 94 votes for. The
new law would allow a court to detain Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok
for up to three years without a trial, instead of the six months
now mandated by a penal law.
</P>
<P>
The new law states that "for the case of crime of genocide, war
crime and crime against humanity in which already mentioned in the
United Nations Convention, the pre-detention can be extended once
a year, but the duration of such extension must not be over three
years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
