<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Key Think-tank Explains Need To Ban Falun Gong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A front-page article in today's
"People's Daily", China's leading newspaper, says that banning the
Falun Dafa Research Society founded by Li Hongzhi was necessary to
support the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
The article, written by a group of researchers at the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) who are studying the Falun Gong
(Falun Dafa) phenomenon, says that the organization jeopardized
society and damaged the laws of the country. The CASS is one of
China's top think-tank and highest research institution of social
sciences.
</P>
<P>
It says that none of Falun Dafa's branches were registered and
that the lives, health, and property of Falun Gong practitioners
had been seriously hurt by Li Hongzhi, concoctor of Falun Gong
whose illegal gatherings disrupted public order.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to ban the group was proper and
legitimate, the researchers say, because the organization violated
the Constitution, civil, criminal, and tax codes, and regulations
for organizations, publishing, assemblies, parades, and
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
They conclude that dealing with Falun Gong in this way shows
reverence for social legislation and was needed for building a
socialist country ruled by law and will provide an education in
socialist legislation for officials and common folk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
