<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coach Ma-absent China Eye One Medal in Athletics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Forget Ma's Family Army, forget
the three gold medals they won at Stuttgart in 1991. China's
goal this time is to get one medal from the 7th World Athletics
Championships, which begins in Seville, Spain, on August 20.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to win a medal of any color," said Shang Xiutang,
General Secretary of the Chinese Athletics Association (CAA).
</P>
<P>
China will send 33 athletes, including 12 men and 21 women, to
compete in 18 events at Seville and their biggest medal chance
lies in the men's and women's 20 kilometers walking events.
</P>
<P>
Liu Hongyu, women's 20km World Cup champion this year, is most
likely to realize China's hope of winning a medal.
</P>
<P>
Liu, ranked second in the world and also the 10km champion in
last year's Bangkok Asian Games, will be joined by teammates Wang
Yan, 1996 Olympic bronze medalist in the 10km event, and Gao
Hongmiao, World Cup 10km champion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"We might not be so strong as Russian opponent individually,
but as a team the three athletes are hard to beat in the 20km
event," Shang said.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 20km walking, Yu Guohui, who finished fourth in
the 1997 Athens World Championships, also has the caliber to take
a medal.
</P>
<P>
Yu has made a remarkable progress in endurance and technique in
the past two years, winning the gold medal in last year's Asian
Games and the silver in the World Cup tournament early this year.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes well, women's long jumper Guang Yingnan,
winner of the Linz Grand Prix in Germany last year with 6.91
meters, is also hopeful to take a medal.
</P>
<P>
In the other events like women's shot put, triple jump and
discus, where Chinese athletes are dominant in Asia, it will be
not bad for them to enter the final eight in Seville, Shang said.
</P>
<P>
"You can not say Chinese athletics has declined just because we
failed to win a gold in the last two championships," Shang said.
</P>
<P>
"In 1991 and 1993, the fact that only a few events got
prosperous did not indicate that China had become a world track
and field powerforce. Our overall strength has been improved in
the past few years though we seldom won a gold in the world
competitions," he added.
</P>
<P>
But as a whole, China, the track and field giant in Asia, will
face the toughest challenge in Seville since early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991 Tokyo meet, China claimed two gold medals through
Xu Demei in the women's javelin and Huang Zhihong in the women's
shot put.
</P>
<P>
In the 1993 Stuttgart championships, legendary coach Ma Junren'
s women runners emerged from nowhere to bag three gold medals in 1,
500-, 3,000- and 10,000 meters. And Huang retained her shot put
title.
</P>
<P>
After the glittering performance in Stuttgart, Chinese
athletics plunged into crises with the breakup of Ma's army. Huang,
who had competed for more than a decade, won a silver in 1995,
which was China's lone medal there.
</P>
<P>
But the 1997 world championships in Athens was more disastrous
for the world's most populous country when they returned home
empty-handed. Ma, who had nurtured a new group of runners, refused
to go to Athens but to save strength for the Chinese Eighth
National Games held two months later.
</P>
<P>
The world-famed coach finally surprised the world in the
National Games, where his two proteges, Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei
broke the world women's 5,000 meters record.
</P>
<P>
But a row broke out between Ma and the CAA because the coach
did not want to compete in the 1998 national Grand Prix, which CAA
ruled as a precondition to qualify for the Asian Games and other
major international meets.
</P>
<P>
Ma and his runners had to stay at home during the Asian Games
last December, but this year they made concession to the country's
governing body CAA and appeared in the field after a layoff of 18
months.
</P>
<P>
However, their comeback was like a nightmare. Among over 10
runners from Ma's training camp, Dong Yanmei was the only one
qualifying for the Grand Prix Finals in Shanghai, where she
finished a humiliating seventh place.
</P>
<P>
But Shang said: "Perhaps Ma does not want to take part in the
World Championships. Like 1997, he is resting his runners in a bid
to make a surprise in the National City Games at Xi'an in
September."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Ma is still upset with the humiliation
that the CAA denied him a chance to compete in the Bangkok Games.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Ma hopes to embarrass the CAA officials by
watching them experience another medal-free world championships
but breaking world records again in a home meet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
