<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tomb Found in Northwest China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered an ancient imperial tomb dating back to the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644) in the southern suburbs of Xi'an, capital of
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Located at Jinfutuo Village, the tomb's occupant was a member
of the imperial family, according to one expert, as confirmed by a
plated identification seal in the tomb chamber.
</P>
<P>
Also at the site, more than 80 historical relics including
colored terra-cotta figures and pottery articles for daily use
such as stove, suitcase, and chair, have been unearthed.
</P>
<P>
With bright colors and vivid artistry, the terra-cotta figures
are in standing and riding postures, said the expert, adding that
they are of great value for the study of ancient culture.
</P>
<P>
It has also been learned that five villagers involved in
robbing the tomb were arrested, and the cultural relics they took
have been recovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
