<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Elephant Tusk Found in Turkmenistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- A section of an ancient
elephant tusk has been found on the bank of the Amu Darya river in
Turkmenistan, a central Asian country known for its vast desert
land.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Turkmen Telegraph Agency on
Tuesday, preliminary appraisals by paleontologists established
that the bone-like piece, measuring 23 centimeters long and 13
centimeters wide, belonged to the tusk of an elephant living some
60,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was the latest in a series of evidences found in
Turkmenistan that prove the living of ancient pachyderms in the
area. The first such remains were discovered in the country in
1945.
</P>
<P>
Paleontologists believe that the Amu Darya river basin was
covered by a thick forest and a rich vegetation 60,000 years ago,
where various animals roamed, including elephants.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan is a land-locked country with 80 of its territory
in the huge Karakumy desert. The country is one of the driest
spots on the earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
