<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission Urged to Implement Resolution on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia on Tuesday accused
the U.N. mission and the international peacekeepers in Kosovo of
failing to fully implement the related U.N. resolution on Kosovo,
which it said has caused "a fairly complicated and serious
situation" in the province.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo has become "very complicated and
serious" as the U.N. special mission and the peacekeeping force
did not earnestly implement the resolution adopted earlier by the
U.N. Security Council, said Zoran Andelkovic, chairman of Kosovo's
Provisional Executive Committee, in Pristina, capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Executive Committee, created in September 1998
to oversee the work of the then local government in Kosovo, is
composed of 18 representatives from all ethnic groups in the
southeastern province of Yugoslavia's Serbian Republic.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with a group of Russian parliamentarians,
Andelkovic said the international peace-keepers rendered the
border between Kosovo and Albania un-defended after the withdrawal
of the Yugoslav military and police forces from the province in
late June.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, a large number of Albanian citizens
entered Kosovo illegally and the population of ethnic Albanians in
Pristina tripled the figure before the NATO bombing of the
province.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission should cooperate with the delegation of the
Serbian government in Kosovo if it really wants to bring peace to
the region, Andelkovic said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the U.N. mission and the international peace-
keepers should unremittingly carry out the U.N. resolution and
respect the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
