<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Supply Route Opened in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A 56-km-long new supply route
through northern Sri Lanka has been opened, enabling travel and
transport between areas controlled by security forces and Tamil
rebels, newspapers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the new land route ended a six-week deadlock
over a safe passage for civilians between the security forces and
the rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The 32-km road between Vavuniya and Mankulam goes through
security forces-cleared areas while the 24 km section from
Mankulam to Kilinochchi is held by the Tamil rebels, the official
Daily News said.
</P>
<P>
For many years the route was closed with the LTTE rebels
refusing to allow a passage.
</P>
<P>
The government has traditionally supplied food and other items
to civilians in rebel-held areas.
</P>
<P>
An earlier route was closed in May when the army launched a
fresh offensive against the LTTE rebels who have been fighting for
a homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since
1983.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the new land route was achieved with the
intervention of the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) in agreement with the LTTE rebels, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the first convoy of 10 buses with 412 civilians who
had been stranded and 10 truckloads of food commodities were
driven along the road escorted by the military while rebel cadres
lined the route a distance away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
