<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, August 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Tuesday called on India and
Pakistan to restrain themselves and solve differences through
dialogue after a Pakistani plane was shot down by India.
</P>
<P>
"In ascertaining the facts, the message that we will be sending
and probably have sent by now is to urge restraint, because we don
't want to see the situation grow and we want the two sides to
resolve their differences through dialogue," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing. (US-S.Asia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday
voiced his relief that all United Nations and West African
peacekeepers had been released by a group of Sierra Leonean rebels
and called on all parties concerned to ensure there was no
repetition.
</P>
<P>
"With the resolution of this deplorable episode, all Sierra
Leoneans and the international community should now look ahead and
devote all energies to the implementation of the Lome Peace
Agreement," Annan said in a statement issued here through his
spokesman. (UN-Sierra Leone-Hostages)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States would not stop hitting Iraqi
military sites despite Wednesday's eclipse of the sun, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said U.S. and British
warplanes patrolling no-fly zones in northern and southern Iraq
would continue their attacks on Iraqi military sites when
encountering challenges from Iraq's defense system. (US-Iraq-
Strikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain on Tuesday urged India and Pakistan to avoid
further provocation and misunderstanding after India shot down a
Pakistani maritime aircraft.
</P>
<P>
"We regret the loss of life. We are urging India and Pakistan
to take the greatest care to avoid provocation and
misunderstanding," a British Foreign Office spokesman said. (UK-
India-Pakistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton urged the nation
Tuesday to "intensify our resolve to make America a better place"
in the face of shooting in Los Angeles and suggested the shootings
again showed the need for tighter gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
"Once again, our nation has been shaken and our hearts torn by
an act of gun violence," Clinton said at a press conference at the
White House. (US-Clinton-Shooting) 
</P>
</TEXT>
