<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Bankruptcies Drop for First Time Since 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of Americans who
filed bankruptcy declined 2 percent during the 12 months ending
June 30, the first yearly decrease since 1995, the Administrative
Office of the U.S. Courts reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Personal bankruptcies in the year mentioned, numbering 1,352,
030, accounted for 97 percent of the total 1,391,964 new
bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
New bankruptcies filed during the second quarter of 1999
dropped to 345,956 from a record 373,460 during the quarter a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
"While bankruptcy filings are still very high, the trend over
the past six months suggests that 1999 will fall short of last
year's record pace," said Sam Gerdano, executive director of the
American Bankruptcy Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
