<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Mineral Output to Increase 11 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Chile's mineral output is
expected to surge 11 percent this year compared with 1998,
president of the National Mineral Society (SONAMI) Herman
Hochschild said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chile will produce 4.25 million tons of pure copper, 42 tons of
gold and 1,370 tons of silver by the end of this year, said
Hochschild.
</P>
<P>
According to SONAMI, the average copper price is currently 65 U.
S. cents per pound, the lowest since 1935, representing a 17
percent fall compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Gold price dropped 6 percent and silver fell 13 percent
compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
Chile, the largest copper producer in the world, will produce 4.
47 million tons of copper in 2000, or 5 percent more than this
year. The SONAMI is hoping that copper price will hover between 75
cents to 80 cents per pound then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
