<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Foreign Banks Ready to Guarantee L/Cs Opened by Indonesian Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- As many as 15 foreign banks are
ready to guarantee Letters of Credit (L/Cs) opened by Indonesian
foreign exchange banks in the name of Bank Ekspor Indonesia (BEI).
</P>
<P>
BEI's commissioner Mukhlis Rasyid said that the 15 foreign
banks include Standard Chartered Bank, Citibank, Deutsche Bank,
ABC Bank and a number of banks grouped in Japan Export Import Bank
(Jexim).
</P>
<P>
"These 15 banks will act as confirming banks for letters of
credit issued by BEI to finance the imports of local export
companies," he was quoted by national newspapers Wednesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
BEI was established in May by the government to support
export-oriented companies.
</P>
<P>
Unlike a conventional bank, BEI will raise funds from
international financing agencies like Jexim rather than the public
to finance its activities.
</P>
<P>
BEI's main tasks will be to guarantee L/Cs and issue guarantees
for domestic exporters who need loans from local banks to finance
their operations.
</P>
<P>
"BEI will begin operating on September 1," Mukhlis said. BEI
was previously slated to begin operations earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Objective Assessment of Its Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Tuesday that
one and half million Iraqis have died as a result of the nine-year
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 children are dying every month due to malnutrition
and lack of medications, said Iraq's Permanent Mission to the
United Nations in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The devastating long-term effects of the radiation resulting
from the depleted uranium weapons used by the American and British
forces in Iraq are beginning to take their toll on the population,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The embargo on the Iraqi economy has brought down Iraq's GDP to
no more than one third of its pre-1991 level and "has effectively
cornered the Iraqi population into a seemingly endless situation
of hunger, deprivation and lack of prospect," the mission said.
</P>
<P>
It accused the United States and Britain of continuing to
interfere into its internal affairs and threaten its territorial
integrity and of continuing to obstruct any move in the Security
Council to render justice to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Declaring that Iraq has fulfilled U.N. requirements for its
disarmament, the mission said Iraq "demands nothing more than the
application of the resolutions of the council legally and fairly,
which requires the objective assessment of the record of
implementation by Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Iraq on August
6, 1990, against its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
