<DOCNO> XIE19990811.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welsh Tory Leader Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Rod Richards has resigned as the
leader of the Conservative Party in Wales, the BBC reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Richards said in a statement that he felt he was left with no
choice after being "undermined" by his party members.
</P>
<P>
His announcement followed the news that Nick Bourne, his former
rival, had been named the new acting leader of the Tory members of
the National Assembly for Wales.
</P>
<P>
Richards had recommended 29-year-old David Davies to be the
deputy leader but was rejected by the Tory members who believed
Davies was "too inexperienced."
</P>
<P>
"I asked the Tory group to endorse my appointment of David
Davies," he said in the statement. "They did not do so. I
therefore feel my authority as leader has been undermined and I
have no alternative but to resign."
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Bourne as acting leader was made at a
Conservative party meeting in Cardiff, just hours before Richards'
resignation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
